{"title_page": "Fitch Poole", "text_new": "'''Fitch Poole''' (1803-1873)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.findagrave.com/memorial/74265773/fitch-poole|title=Fitch Poole Memorial|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>, also known as '''Fitch Poole Jr.''' or '''Fitch Poole Junior''', was an American journalist, humorist and politician.\n\n== Biography ==\nPoole Jr. was born 13 June 1803 in [[Salem, Massachusetts|Salem]], [[Massachusetts]] (renamed [[Peabody, Massachusetts|Peabody]] after 1868), and was the son of Fitch Poole and Elizabeth Poole (Cutler). He was named after his father. Poole Jr. also had 3 other siblings, and one nephew.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.findagrave.com/memorial/49277998/leonard-poole|title=Leonard Poole|last=|first=|date=|website=Find a Grave|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> \n\nPoole Jr. was closely associated with the press and is notably known for being the editor of the [[Danvers, Massachusetts|Danvers]]-based newspaper titled \"Wizard\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://archive.org/details/TheSouthDanversWizard18591860/page/n23/mode/2up%20%22The%20South%20Danver%20Wizards%22|title=The South Danver Wizard|last=|first=|date=|website=Archieve.org|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> He held this position for about 19 years.\n\nFitch Poole Jr. was the president of Denver's Mechanic Institute (which afterward became known as the \"[[Peabody Institute (Danvers, Massachusetts)|Peabody Institute]]\") from 1844 until 1853.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://peabodyinstitutearchives.tumblr.com/post/174632073693/a-letter-from-fitch-poole-who-was-the-president|title=Fitch Poole letter as President|last=|first=|date=|website=Peabodyinstitutyarchives|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sutori.com/story/timeline-of-the-peabody-institute-library-41a1|title=Timeline of Peabody Institute Library|last=|first=|date=|website=Suitori|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> He was also the founder of the Mechanics' Insitute library, and held the librarian position of the institute for about 17 years.<ref>{{Cite web|url=famousamericans.net/fitchpoole/|title=Fitch Poole Biography|last=|first=|date=|website=Famous Americans|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nPoole was the author of different satirical ballads.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://worldcat.org/identities/lccn-nr93037756/|title=Fitch Poole Bibliography|last=|first=|date=|website=World cat|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> One of his most well-known ballads is the \"Giles Corey's Dream\", whitch attracted a lot of interest.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://newenglandfolklore.blogspot.com/2015/05/the-ballad-of-giles-corey-its.html?m=1|title=The ballad of Giles Corey Analysis|last=|first=|date=|website=New England Folklore|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=worldcat.com/title/giles-coreys-dream/oclc/843870825|title=Giles Corey's Dream|last=|first=|date=|website=World Cat|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nPoole Jr. was the cousin of the surveyor, civil engineer, and educator [[Henry Ward Poole]], and he was also the cousin of the famous bibliographer and librarian [[William Frederick Poole]].\n\nPoole died 19 August 1873 at the age of 70 in [[Peabody, Massachusetts|Peabody]] and is burried in the same place.<ref>{{Cite web|url=prabook.com/web/flich.poole/1089577|title=Fitch Poole|last=|first=|date=|website=Prabook|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n", "text_old": "'''Fitch Poole''' (1803-1873)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.findagrave.com/memorial/74265773/fitch-poole|title=Fitch Poole Memorial|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>, also known as '''Fitch Poole Jr.''' or '''Fitch Poole Junior''', was an American journalist, humorist and politician.\n\n== Biography ==\nPoole Jr. was born 13 June 1803 in [[Salem, Massachusetts|Salem]], [[Massachusetts]] (renamed [[Peabody, Massachusetts|Peabody]] after 1868), and was the son of Fitch Poole and Elizabeth Poole (Cutler). He was named after his father. Poole Jr. also had 3 other siblings, and one nephew.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.findagrave.com/memorial/49277998/leonard-poole|title=Leonard Poole|last=|first=|date=|website=Find a Grave|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> \n\nPoole Jr. was closely associated with the press and is notably known for being the editor of the [[Danvers, Massachusetts|Danvers]]-based newspaper titled \"Wizard\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://archive.org/details/TheSouthDanversWizard18591860/page/n23/mode/2up%20%22The%20South%20Danver%20Wizards%22|title=The South Danver Wizard|last=|first=|date=|website=Archieve.org|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> He held this position for about 19 years.\n\nFitch Poole Jr. was the president of Denver's Mechanic Institute (which afterward became known as the \"[[Peabody Institute (Danvers, Massachusetts)|Peabody Institute]]\") from 1844 until 1853.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://peabodyinstitutearchives.tumblr.com/post/174632073693/a-letter-from-fitch-poole-who-was-the-president|title=Fitch Poole letter as President|last=|first=|date=|website=Peabodyinstitutyarchives|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sutori.com/story/timeline-of-the-peabody-institute-library-41a1|title=Timeline of Peabody Institute Library|last=|first=|date=|website=Suitori|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> He was also the founder of the Mechanics' Insitute library, and held the librarian position of the institute for about 17 years.<ref>{{Cite web|url=famousamericans.net/fitchpoole/|title=Fitch Poole Biography|last=|first=|date=|website=Famous Americans|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nPoole was the author of different satirical ballads.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://worldcat.org/identities/lccn-nr93037756/|title=Fitch Poole Bibliography|last=|first=|date=|website=World cat|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> One of his most well-known ballads is the \"Giles Corey's Dream\", whitch attracted a lot of interest.<ref>{{Cite web|url=newenglandfolklore.blogspot.com/2015/05/the-ballad-of-giles-corey-its.html|title=The Ballad of Giles Corey: It's complicated...|last=Muise|first=Peter|date=|website=New England Folklore|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=worldcat.com/title/giles-coreys-dream/oclc/843870825|title=Giles Corey's Dream|last=|first=|date=|website=World Cat|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nPoole Jr. was the cousin of the surveyor, civil engineer, and educator [[Henry Ward Poole]], and he was also the cousin of the famous bibliographer and librarian [[William Frederick Poole]].\n\nPoole died 19 August 1873 at the age of 70 in [[Peabody, Massachusetts|Peabody]] and is burried in the same place.<ref>{{Cite web|url=prabook.com/web/flich.poole/1089577|title=Fitch Poole|last=|first=|date=|website=Prabook|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n", "name_user": "Jam ai qe ju shikoni", "label": "safe", "comment": "Made citation clearer", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fitch_Poole"}
{"title_page": "Agenda, Kansas", "text_new": "{{Infobox settlement\n|name                     = Agenda, Kansas\n|settlement_type          = [[City]]\n\n<!-- Images -->\n|image_skyline            = \n|image_caption            = \n|image_flag               = \n|image_seal               =\n\n<!-- Maps -->\n|image_map                = Republic_County_Kansas_Incorporated_and_Unincorporated_areas_Agenda_Highlighted.svg\n|map_caption              = Location within [[Republic County, Kansas|Republic County]] and [[Kansas]]\n|image_map1               = Map of Republic Co, Ks, USA.png\n|map_caption1             = [[Kansas Department of Transportation|KDOT]] map of [[Republic County, Kansas|Republic County]] ([[:File:Kansas official transportation map legend.png|legend]])\n\n<!-- Location -->\n|coordinates_footnotes    =\n|coordinates              = {{coord|39|42|32|N|97|25|56|W|region:US-KS_type:city|display=inline,title}}\n|subdivision_type         = [[List of sovereign states|Country]]\n|subdivision_name         = United States\n|subdivision_type1        = [[U.S. state|State]]\n|subdivision_name1        = [[Kansas]]\n|subdivision_type2        = [[List of counties in Kansas|County]]\n|subdivision_name2        = [[Republic County, Kansas|Republic]]\n|subdivision_type3        = [[List of townships in Kansas|Township]]\n|subdivision_name3        =\n\n<!-- Established -->\n|established_title        = Founded\n|established_date         = 1880s\n|established_title1       = [[Platted]]\n|established_date1        = 1887\n|established_title2       = [[Municipal corporation|Incorporated]]\n|established_date2        = 1916\n|named_for                =\n\n<!-- Government -->\n|government_footnotes     = \n|government_type          = <!-- [[Mayor\u2013council government|Mayor\u2013Council]] -->\n|leader_title             = [[Mayor]]\n|leader_name              =\n\n<!-- Area -->\n|area_footnotes           = <ref name=\"CenPopGazetteer2016\">{{cite web|title=2018 U.S. Gazetteer Files|url=https://www2.census.gov/geo/docs/maps-data/data/gazetteer/2018_Gazetteer/2018_gaz_place_20.txt|publisher=United States Census Bureau|accessdate=Nov 1, 2019}}</ref>\n|area_total_sq_mi         = 0.17\n|area_land_sq_mi          = 0.17\n|area_water_sq_mi         = 0.00\n|area_total_km2           = 0.45\n|area_land_km2            = 0.45\n|area_water_km2           = 0.00\n|unit_pref                = Imperial\n\n<!-- Elevation -->\n|elevation_footnotes      =\n|elevation_ft             = 1414\n\n<!-- Population -->\n|population_footnotes     = <ref name=\"FactFinder\"/>\n|population_as_of         = [[2010 United States Census|2010]]\n|population_total         = 68\n|pop_est_footnotes        = <ref name=\"USCensusEst2018\"/>\n|pop_est_as_of            = 2018\n|population_est           = 66\n|population_density_sq_mi = auto\n\n<!-- General information -->\n|timezone                 = [[Central Time Zone|CST]]\n|utc_offset               = -6\n|timezone_DST             = CDT\n|utc_offset_DST           = -5\n|postal_code_type         = [[ZIP code]]\n|postal_code              = 66930\n|area_code_type           = [[North American Numbering Plan|Area code]]\n|area_code                = [[Area code 785|785]]\n|blank_name               = [[Federal Information Processing Standard|FIPS code]]\n|blank_info               = 20-00475 <ref name=\"GR2\">{{cite web|url=http://factfinder2.census.gov |publisher=[[United States Census Bureau]] |accessdate=2008-01-31 |title=American FactFinder |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130911234518/http://factfinder2.census.gov/ |archivedate=2013-09-11 }}</ref>\n|blank1_name              = [[Geographic Names Information System|GNIS ID]]\n|blank1_info              = 0473107 <ref name=\"GR3\">{{cite web|url=http://geonames.usgs.gov|accessdate=2008-01-31|title=US Board on Geographic Names|publisher=[[United States Geological Survey]]|date=2007-10-25}}</ref>\n|website                  =\n}}\n\n'''Agenda''' is a city in [[Republic County, Kansas|Republic County]], [[Kansas]], United States.  As of the [[2010 United States Census|2010 census]], the city population was 68.<ref name=\"Census2010\">{{cite web|title=2010 City Population and Housing Occupancy Status |url=http://factfinder2.census.gov/faces/tableservices/jsf/pages/productview.xhtml?pid=DEC_10_PL_GCTPL2.ST13&prodType=table |publisher=U.S. Census Bureau |accessdate=October 18, 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110721034521/http://factfinder2.census.gov/faces/tableservices/jsf/pages/productview.xhtml?pid=DEC_10_PL_GCTPL2.ST13&prodType=table |archivedate=July 21, 2011 }}</ref>\n\n==History==\nAgenda (formerly '''Neva''') was laid out in 1887 on the [[Chicago, Rock Island and Pacific Railroad]] line.<ref>{{cite book | url=https://archive.org/details/historyofrepubli02sava | title=A History of Republic County, Kansas | publisher=Jones & Chubbic | author=Savage, Isaac O. | year=1901 | pages=[https://archive.org/details/historyofrepubli02sava/page/192 192]}}</ref><ref>{{cite book | url=https://archive.org/details/bub_gb_o8X5krq3fP8C | title=Kansas: A Cyclopedia of State History, Embracing Events, Institutions, Industries, Counties, Cities, Towns, Prominent Persons, Etc. | publisher=Standard Publishing Company | author=Blackmar, Frank Wilson | year=1912 | pages=[https://archive.org/details/bub_gb_o8X5krq3fP8C/page/n28 32]}}</ref> The name Agenda derives from Latin meaning \"what ought to be done\".<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.epodunk.com/cgi-bin/genInfo.php?locIndex=4412 | title=Profile for Agenda, Kansas | publisher=[[ePodunk]] | accessdate=21 June 2014}}</ref>\n\nThe first house in Agenda was erected by Joseph Cox in 1887.  In the early 1900s, it had a money order post office with one rural delivery route, express and telegraph offices, several general stores and other business establishments, a bank, a grain elevator, and in 1910 reported a population of 200. <ref>{{cite book | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=o8X5krq3fP8C&pg=PA132#v=onepage&q&f=false | title=Kansas: A Cyclopedia of State History, Embracing Events, Institutions, Industries, Counties, Cities, Towns, Prominent Persons, Etc. | publisher=Standard Publishing Company | author=Blackmar, Frank Wilson | year=1912</ref>\n\nThe post office in Agenda was discontinued in 1998.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kshs.org/geog/geog_postoffices/search/county:RP |title=Kansas Post Offices, 1828-1961 |publisher=Kansas Historical Society |accessdate=21 June 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131009123556/http://www.kshs.org/geog/geog_postoffices/search/county%3ARP |archivedate=October 9, 2013 }}</ref>\n\n==Geography==\nAgenda is located at {{coord|39|42|32|N|97|25|56|W|type:city}} (39.708897, -97.432156).<ref name=\"GR1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/geo/www/gazetteer/gazette.html|publisher=[[United States Census Bureau]]|accessdate=2011-04-23|date=2011-02-12|title=US Gazetteer files: 2010, 2000, and 1990}}</ref>  According to the [[United States Census Bureau]], the city has a total area of {{convert|0.15|sqmi|sqkm|2}}, all of it land.<ref name=\"Gazetteer files\">{{cite web|title=US Gazetteer files 2010 |url=https://www.census.gov/geo/www/gazetteer/files/Gaz_places_national.txt |publisher=[[United States Census Bureau]] |accessdate=2012-07-06 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120125061959/http://www.census.gov/geo/www/gazetteer/files/Gaz_places_national.txt |archivedate=2012-01-25 }}</ref>\n\n==Demographics==\n{{US Census population\n|align=left\n|1920= 239\n|1930= 185\n|1940= 179\n|1950= 159\n|1960= 124\n|1970= 107\n|1980= 106\n|1990= 81\n|2000= 81\n|2010= 68\n|estyear=2018\n|estimate=66\n|estref=<ref name=\"USCensusEst2018\">{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/programs-surveys/popest/data/tables.2018.html|title=Population and Housing Unit Estimates|accessdate=June 4, 2019}}</ref>\n|align-fn=center\n|footnote=[https://www.census.gov/prod/www/abs/decennial/ U.S. Decennial Census]\n}}\n\n===2010 census===\nAs of the [[census]]<ref name =\"FactFinder\">{{cite web|title=American FactFinder|url=http://factfinder2.census.gov/faces/nav/jsf/pages/index.xhtml|publisher=[[United States Census Bureau]]|accessdate=2012-07-06}}</ref> of 2010, there were 68 people, 29 households, and 18 families living in the city. The [[population density]] was {{convert|453.3|PD/sqmi|PD/km2|1}}. There were 52 housing units at an average density of {{convert|346.7|/sqmi|/km2|1}}. The racial makeup of the city was 97.1% [[White (U.S. Census)|White]] and 2.9% from two or more races.\n\nThere were 29 households of which 24.1% had children under the age of 18 living with them, 58.6% were [[Marriage|married couples]] living together, 3.4% had a female householder with no husband present, and 37.9% were non-families. 37.9% of all households were made up of individuals and 17.2% had someone living alone who was 65 years of age or older. The average household size was 2.34 and the average family size was 3.11.\n\nThe median age in the city was 42 years. 25% of residents were under the age of 18; 4.5% were between the ages of 18 and 24; 22% were from 25 to 44; 23.5% were from 45 to 64; and 25% were 65 years of age or older. The gender makeup of the city was 51.5% male and 48.5% female.\n\n===2000 census===\nAs of the [[census]]<ref name=\"GR2\" /> of 2000, there were 81 people, 38 households, and 24 families living in the city. The [[population density]] was 534.5 people per square mile (208.5/km\u00b2). There were 54 housing units at an average density of 356.3 per square mile (139.0/km\u00b2). The racial makeup of the city was 100.00% [[White (U.S. Census)|White]].\n\nThere were 38 households out of which 23.7% had children under the age of 18 living with them, 57.9% were [[Marriage|married couples]] living together, 2.6% had a female householder with no husband present, and 36.8% were non-families. 36.8% of all households were made up of individuals and 15.8% had someone living alone who was 65 years of age or older. The average household size was 2.13 and the average family size was 2.75.\n\nIn the city, the population was spread out with 22.2% under the age of 18, 4.9% from 18 to 24, 23.5% from 25 to 44, 18.5% from 45 to 64, and 30.9% who were 65 years of age or older. The median age was 44 years. For every 100 females, there were 88.4 males. For every 100 females age 18 and over, there were 80.0 males.\n\nThe median income for a household in the city was $26,500, and the median income for a family was $39,063. Males had a median income of $31,250 versus $11,250 for females. The [[per capita income]] for the city was $13,307. There were no families and 5.9% of the population living below the [[poverty line]], including no under eighteens and 6.1% of those over 64.\n\n==Education==\nAgenda is served by [[Unified School District|USD]] 109 Republic County located in [[Belleville, Kansas|Belleville]]. The Republic County High School mascot is Republic County Buffaloes.\n\nAgenda schools were closed through school unification. The Agenda High School mascot was Huskies.<ref>\"Agenda Huskies Capture Republican Valley Title\", The Salina Journal, 17 November 1960, p.22.</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n{{See also|Republic County, Kansas#Further reading|l1=List of books about Republic County, Kansas}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Portal|Kansas}}\n;City\n* [https://www.lkm.org/members/?id=41260510 Agenda - Directory of Public Officials]\n;Schools\n* [http://www.usd109.org USD 109], local school district\n;Maps\n* [http://www.ksdot.org/Assets/wwwksdotorg/bureaus/burTransPlan/maps/city-pdf/agenda.pdf Agenda City Map], KDOT\n\n{{Republic County, Kansas}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n[[Category:Cities in Kansas]]\n[[Category:Cities in Republic County, Kansas]]\n[[Category:1887 establishments in Kansas]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox settlement\n|name                     = Agenda, Kansas\n|settlement_type  