{"title_page": "History of African presence in London", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2013}}\n{{More citations needed|date=January 2008}}\n[[File:FourTimesNoon.jpg|thumb|upright=1.25|right|[[William Hogarth]]'s engraving ''[[Four Times of the Day#Noon|Four Times of the Day: Noon]]'' (1738) shows a black London resident.]]\nThere is evidence of the '''[[Africa]]n presence in [[London]]''', [[England]], from [[Imperial Rome|Roman]] times to the present day.\n\n== Roman London ==\nUsing [[bioarchaeology]], DNA analysis and the examination of [[grave goods]] in [[Roman London|Roman London]] have identified one woman from the southern Mediterranean that may have had black African ancestry who had both travelled to London during the Roman period.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Redfern|first1=Rebecca|last2=DeWitte|first2=Sharon|last3=Montgomery|first3=Janet|last4=Gowland|first4=Rebecca|title=A Novel Investigation into Migrant and Local Health-Statuses in the Past: A Case Study from Roman Britain|journal=Bioarcheology International|date=November 1, 2018|volume=2|issue=1|doi=10.5744/bi.2018.1014}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Poinar|first=Hendrik N.|last2=Eaton|first2=Katherine|last3=Marshall|first3=Michael|last4=Redfern|first4=Rebecca C.|date=2017|title='Written in Bone': New Discoveries about the Lives and Burials of Four Roman Londoners|journal=Britannia|language=en|volume=48|pages=253\u2013277|doi=10.1017/S0068113X17000216|issn=0068-113X}}</ref>\n\n== 16th century ==\nEarly in the 16th century, Africans arrived in London when [[Catherine of Aragon]] travelled to London and brought a group of her African attendants with her{{Citation needed|date=January 2008}}.  Around the same time Africans named trumpeters, who served [[Henry VII of England|Henry VII]] and [[Henry VIII of England|Henry VIII]], came to London when trade lines began to open between London and West Africa. The first record of an African in London was in 1593. His name was Cornelius. London's residents started to become fearful of the increased black population.  At this time [[Elizabeth I of England|Elizabeth I]] declared that black \"Negroes and black [[Moors]]\" were to be arrested and expelled from her kingdom, although this did not lead to any known legislation.<ref>{{cite journal |url=http://www.accessmylibrary.com/coms2/summary_0286-15698891_ITM |title=Too many Blackamoors: deportation, discrimination, and Elizabeth I |first=Emily |last=Bartels |journal=SEL: Studies in English Literature 1500\u20131900 |date=22 March 2006 |access-date= }}</ref><ref>{{cite book |authorlink = |first =  Carole Boyce| last = Davies |title = Encyclopedia of the African diaspora: origins, experiences, and culture |isbn = 978-1-85109-700-5 |publisher = ABC-CLIO Ltd  |year = 2008 }}</ref>\n\n== 17th\u201318th centuries ==\nDuring this era there was a  small rise of black people arriving in London. Britain was involved with the [[Atlantic slave trade|tri-continental slave trade]] between Europe, Africa and the Americas.  Black slaves were attendants to sea captains and ex-colonial officials as well as traders, plantation owners and military personnel. This marked growing evidence of the black presence in the northern, eastern and southern areas of London. There were also small numbers of free slaves and seaman from West Africa and South Asia. Many of these people were forced into beggary due to the lack of jobs and racial discrimination.<ref>Banton, Michael (1955), ''The Coloured Quarter''. Jonathan Cape. London.</ref><ref>{{cite book|last=Shyllon|first=Folarin|chapter=The Black Presence and Experience in Britain: An Analytical Overview|editor-first=Jagdish S.|editor-last=Gundara|editor-first2=Ian|editor-last2=Duffield|date=1992|title=Essays on the History of Blacks in Britain|publisher=Avebury|location=Aldershot|isbn=978-1856282130}}</ref> There is evidence that black men and women were occasionally discriminated against when dealing  with the law because of their skin colour. In 1737 George Scipio was accused of stealing Anne Godfrey's washing, the case rested entirely on whether or not Scipio was the only black man in Hackney at the time.<ref>{{Cite web|title = Communities \u2013 Black Communities \u2013 Central Criminal Court|url = https://www.oldbaileyonline.org/static/Black.jsp|website = www.oldbaileyonline.org|access-date = 2016-01-22}}</ref>\n\nAround the 1750s London became the home of many of Black people, Jews, Irish, Germans, and [[Huguenot]]s. In 1764 The Gentleman's Magazine reported that there was 'supposed to be near 20,000 Negroe servants'  -Evidence of the number of black residents in London has been found through registered burials. The people of London had widespread views that Black people in London were less than human;  {{Citation needed|date=January 2011}} these views were expressed in slave sale advertisements. Leading black activists of this era included [[Olaudah Equiano]], [[Ignatius Sancho]] and [[Quobna Ottobah Cugoano]].\nWith the support of other Britons these activists demanded that Blacks be freed from slavery.  Supporters involved in this movements included workers and other nationalities of the urban poor<!-- commented out because non-neutral point of view: who themselves suffered under the rule of the upper class -->. <!--commented out: was the slave trade widely carried on in Britain? Got a source for that?: that was widespread throughout Britain -->.  At this time the slavery of whites was forbidden, but the legal statuses of these practices were not clearly defined.  Free black slaves could not be enslaved, but blacks who were brought as slaves to Britain were considered the property of their owners.\nDuring this era [[Lord Mansfield]] declared that a slave who fled from his master could not be taken by force or sold abroad, in the case of [[Somerset v Stewart]].  This verdict fuelled the numbers of Blacks that escaped slavery, and helped send slavery into decline.  In this same period many slave soldiers who fought on the side of the British in the [[American Revolutionary War]] arrived in London.  These soldiers were deprived of pensions and many of them became poverty-stricken and were reduced to begging on the streets.  The Blacks in London lived among the whites in areas of [[Mile End]], [[Stepney]], [[Paddington]] and [[St Giles, London|St Giles]]. The majority of these people did not live as slaves, but as servants to wealthy whites. Many became labeled as the \"Black Poor\" defined as former low wage soldiers, seafarers and plantation workers.<ref name=\"FilePower\">{{cite book|last=File|first=Nigel|first2=Chris|last2=Power|date=1981|title=Black Settlers in Britain 1555\u20131958|publisher=Heinnemann Educational|isbn=978-0435311735}}</ref>\n\nDuring the late 18th century there were many publications and memoirs written about the \"black poor\".  One example is the writings of Equiano, who became an unofficial spokesman for Britain's Black community.  A memoir about his life is entitled, ''[[The Interesting Narrative of the Life of Olaudah Equiano]]''. Equiano became a landowner in Cambridgeshire and married Susannah Cullen, from [[Soham]]. Both his daughters were born and baptised there.\n\nIn 1787 4,000 blacks were transported from London for resettlement to the colony of Sierra Leone with help from the Committee for the Relief of the Black Poor.<ref>http://www.betterworldbooks.com/african-americans-in-the-american-revolution-id-1155512723.aspx</ref>\n\n== 19th century ==\n\nComing into the early 19th century, more groups of black soldiers and seaman were displaced after the [[Napoleonic wars]] and some settled in London.  These settlers suffered and faced many challenges as did many black people in London.  <!-- (commented out: see [[Atlantic slave trade#Economics of slavery]] for debates about this.) In the late eighteenth century the slave trade declined, as a direct result of industrial [[capitalism]]{{citation needed|date=November 2010}} --><!-- there's debate about this, I've seen arguments that it was at its height just before abolition. Please provide evidence for your claim--> <!-- (commented out: there was only one parliament in Britain!): throughout this early period different parliaments throughout Britain followed suit and --> the slave trade was abolished completely in the British empire by 1834.  The number of blacks in London was steadily declining with these new laws.  Fewer blacks were brought into London from the West Indies and parts of Africa.<ref name=\"FilePower\" />\n\nDuring the mid-19th century there were restrictions on African immigration.  In the later part of the 19th century there was a buildup of small groups of black dockside communities in towns such as [[Canning Town]],<ref>Geoffrey Bell, ''The other Eastenders : Kamal Chunchie and West Ham's early black community'' (Stratford: Eastside Community Heritage, 2002)</ref> [[Liverpool]], and [[Cardiff]].  This was a direct effect of new shipping links that were established with the Caribbean and West Africa.\n\nDespite social prejudice and  racist discrimination in Victorian England, some nineteenth-century black people living in England achieved exceptional success. [[Pablo Fanque]], born poor as William Darby in Norwich, rose to become the proprietor of one of Britain's most successful Victorian circuses. He is immortalised in the lyrics of The Beatles song \"Being for the Benefit of Mr. Kite!\" Another famous black Briton was [[William Davidson (conspirator)|William Davison]], a conspirator executed in London for his role in the Cato Street Conspiracy against Lord Liverpool's government in 1820. Britain's first black [[High Sheriff]] was [[Nathaniel Wells]], the son of a slave from [[St Kitts]] and a slave trader. After his father's death he was freed and inherited a fortune. He moved to Monmouthshire's [[Piercefield House]] and became [[Sheriff of Monmouthshire]] in 1818. One of the leaders in 19th century [[chartism]] was [[William Cuffay]], who was born on a merchant ship in the West Indies in 1788, and whose father, had been a slave in St Kitts.<ref>{{cite web|publisher=BBC|work=History|title=William Cuffay (1788 - 1870)|url= http://www.bbc.co.uk/history/historic_figures/cuffay_william.shtml}}</ref>\n\n==20th century==\n\nOne of the black Londoners, [[Learie Constantine]], a cricketer from Trinidad and  welfare officer in the [[RAF]], was refused service at a London hotel. He stood up for his rights and later was awarded compensation.  That particular example is used by some to illustrate the slow change from racism towards acceptance and equality of all citizens in London.<ref>{{cite journal\n |title   = Race, empire and British wartime national identity, 1939\u201345\n |pages   = 220\u201337\n |first   = Sonya\n |last    = Rose\n |journal = Historical Research\n |volume  = 74\n |issue   = 184\n |date    = May 2001\n |doi     = 10.1111/1468-2281.00125\n|pmid = 18161216\n }}</ref>\n\n=== Post-war period ===\nIn 1950, it was estimated there  were no more than 20,000 non-White residents in the United Kingdom, mainly in England; almost all born overseas.<ref>{{Cite book|title=The Demographic Characteristics of Immigrant Populations|url= https://books.google.com/books?id=mmaRpUa1oSoC|publisher=Council of Europe Publishing|date=2002|isbn=9789287149749|language=en|editor-first=Werner|editor-last=Haug|editor-first2=Paul|editor-last2=Compton|editor-first3=Youssef|editor-last3=Courbage}}</ref> Just after the end of [[World War II]], the first groups of post-war Caribbean immigrants started to emigrate and settle in [[London]]. There were an estimated 492 that were passengers on the {{HMT|Empire Windrush}} that arrived at [[Tilbury Docks]] on 22 June 1948. These passengers settled in the area of [[Brixton]] which is now a prominently Black district in Britain. From the 1950s into the 1960s, there was a mass migration of workers from all over the English-speaking Caribbean, particularly [[Colony of Jamaica|Jamaica]]; who settled in the UK. These immigrants were invited to fill labour requirements in London's hospitals, transportation venues and railway development. There was a continuous influx of African students, sportsmen, and businessmen mixed within British society .<ref>{{Cite web|title = Black British timeline {{!}} Black London {{!}} Black British History|url = http://www.blackpresence.co.uk/black-british-timeline/|website = The Black Presence in Britain|access-date = 2016-02-14|language = en-GB}}</ref>  They are widely viewed as having been a major contributing factor to the rebuilding of the post-war urban London economy.\n\nIn 1962, the [[Commonwealth Immigrants Act 1962|Commonwealth Immigrants Act]] was passed in the UK along with a succession of other laws in [[Commonwealth Immigrants Act 1968|1968]], [[Immigration Act 1971|1971]], and [[British Nationality Act 1981|1981]] that severely restricted the entry of Black Caribbean immigrants into the United Kingdom. During this period, it is widely argued that emergent Blacks and Asians struggled in Britain against racism and prejudice. In 1975, a new voice emerged for the Black population of London; his name was [[David Pitt, Baron Pitt of Hampstead|David Pitt]] and he brought a new voice to the [[House of Lords]]. He spoke against racism and for equality in regards to all residents of Britain. At the [[1987 United Kingdom general election|1987 general election]], the first-ever [[Black British]] MPs were elected to the [[House of Commons]]; [[Diane Abbott]] for [[Hackney North and Stoke Newington (UK Parliament constituency)|Hackney North and Stoke Newington]], [[Bernie Grant]] for [[Tottenham (UK Parliament constituency)|Tottenham]] and [[Paul Boateng]] for [[Brent South (UK Parliament constituency)|Brent South]]. All were candidates from the [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]], and out of these three people; Abbott holds the distinction of being the first Black British woman to be elected to the House of Commons and is also the only one to still be an MP to the present day, as Grant died in 2000 and Boateng stood down in [[2005 United Kingdom general election|2005]].\n\nBy the end of the twentieth century, the number of Black Londoners numbered half a million, according to the [[United Kingdom Census 1991|1991 UK Census]]. An increasing number of these Black Londoners were London, or British-born. Even with this growing population and the first Blacks elected to the UK Parliament, many argue that there was still discrimination and a socio-economic imbalance in London among the Black community. In [[1992 United Kingdom general election|1992]], the number of Blacks in Parliament increased to six and in [[1997 United Kingdom general election|1997]], they increased their numbers to nine. There are still many problems that Black Londoners face; the new global and high-tech information revolution is changing the urban economy and some argue that it is driving unemployment rates among Blacks up relative to non-blacks,{{Citation needed|date=January 2008}} something which, it is argued, threatens to erode the progress made thus far.<ref name=\"FilePower\" />\n\nAs of June 2007, the Black population of London is 802,300, equivalent to 10.6% of the population of London. 4.3% of Londoners are Caribbean, 5.5% of Londoners are African and a further 0.8% are from other black backgrounds including American and Latin American. There are also 117,400 people who are mixed black and white.<ref>[http://www.neighbourhood.statistics.gov.uk/dissemination/LeadTableView.do?a=3&b=276743&c=london&d=13&e=13&g=325264&i=1001x1003x1004&m=0&r=1&s=1217082648365&enc=1&dsFamilyId=1809 Resident Population Estimates by Ethnic Group, All Persons]</ref> At the [[United Kingdom Census 2011|2011 UK Census]], the total Black population of London stood at 1,088,640 or 13.3% of the population.<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://www.ons.gov.uk/ons/rel/census/2011-census/key-statistics-for-local-authorities-in-england-and-wales/rft-table-ks201ew.xls|title = 2011 black population london|date = |access-date = |website = |publisher = |last = |first = }}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n{{Portal|London}}\n*[[Historical immigration to Great Britain]]\n*[[Black British]]\n*[[Ethnic groups in London]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n{{Black British topics}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Arrival Of Black Immigrants in London}}\n[[Category:Black British culture in London]]\n[[Category:Black British history]]\n[[Category:History of immigration to the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:History of London|African]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2013}}\n{{More citations needed|date=January 2008}}\n[[File:FourTimesNoon.jpg|thumb|upright=1.25|right|[[William Hogarth]]'s engraving ''[[Four Times of the Day#Noon|Four Times of the Day: Noon]]'' (1738) shows a black London resident.]]\nThere is evidence of the '''[[Africa]]n presence in [[London]]''', [[England]], from [[Imperial Rome|Roman]] times to the present day.\n\n== Roman London ==\nUsing [[bioarchaeology]], DNA analysis and the examination of [[grave goods]] in [[Roman London|Roman London]] have identified one woman from the southern Mediterranean that may have had black African ancestry who had both travelled to London during the Roman period.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Redfern|first1=Rebecca|last2=DeWitte|first2=Sharon|last3=Montgomery|first3=Janet|last4=Gowland|first4=Rebecca|title=A Novel Investigation into Migrant and Local Health-Statuses in the Past: A Case Study from Roman Britain|journal=Bioarcheology International|date=November 1, 2018|volume=2|issue=1|doi=10.5744/bi.2018.1014}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Poinar|first=Hendrik N.|last2=Eaton|first2=Katherine|last3=Marshall|first3=Michael|last4=Redfern|first4=Rebecca C.|date=2017|title='Written in Bone': New Discoveries about the Lives and Burials of Four Roman Londoners|journal=Britannia|language=en|volume=48|pages=253\u2013277|doi=10.1017/S0068113X17000216|issn=0068-113X}}</ref>\n\n== 16th century ==\nEarly in the 16th century, Africans arrived in London when [[Catherine of Aragon]] travelled to London and brought a group of her African attendants with her{{Citation needed|date=January 2008}}.  Around the same time Africans named trumpeters, who served [[Henry VII of England|Henry VII]] and [[Henry VIII of England|Henry VIII]], came to London when trade lines began to open between London and West Africa. The first record of an African in London was in 1593. His name was Cornelius. London\u2019s residents started to become fearful of the increased black population.  At this time [[Elizabeth I of England|Elizabeth I]] declared that black \"Negroes and black [[Moors]]\" were to be arrested and expelled from her kingdom, although this did not lead to any known legislation.<ref>{{cite journal |url=http://www.accessmylibrary.com/coms2/summary_0286-15698891_ITM |title=Too many Blackamoors: deportation, discrimination, and Elizabeth I |first=Emily |last=Bartels |journal=SEL: Studies in English Literature 1500\u20131900 |date=22 March 2006 |access-date= }}</ref><ref>{{cite book |authorlink = |first =  Carole Boyce| last = Davies |title = Encyclopedia of the African diaspora: origins, experiences, and culture |isbn = 978-1-85109-700-5 |publisher = ABC-CLIO Ltd  |year = 2008 }}</ref>\n\n== 17th\u201318th centuries ==\nDuring this era there was a  small rise of black people arriving in London. Britain was involved with the [[Atlantic slave trade|tri-continental slave trade]] between Europe, Africa and the Americas.  Black slaves were attendants to sea captains and ex-colonial officials as well as traders, plantation owners and military personnel. This marked growing evidence of the black presence in the northern, eastern and southern areas of London. There were also small numbers of free slaves and seaman from West Africa and South Asia. Many of these people were forced into beggary due to the lack of jobs and racial discrimination.<ref>Banton, Michael (1955), ''The Coloured Quarter''. Jonathan Cape. London.</ref><ref>{{cite book|last=Shyllon|first=Folarin|chapter=The Black Presence and Experience in Britain: An Analytical Overview|editor-first=Jagdish S.|editor-last=Gundara|editor-first2=Ian|editor-last2=Duffield|date=1992|title=Essays on the History of Blacks in Britain|publisher=Avebury|location=Aldershot|isbn=978-1856282130}}</ref> There is evidence that black men and women were occasionally discriminated against when dealing  with the law because of their skin colour. In 1737 George Scipio was accused of stealing Anne Godfrey's washing, the case rested entirely on whether or not Scipio was the only black man in Hackney at the time.<ref>{{Cite web|title = Communities \u2013 Black Communities \u2013 Central Criminal Court|url = https://www.oldbaileyonline.org/static/Black.jsp|website = www.oldbaileyonline.org|access-date = 2016-01-22}}</ref>\n\nAround the 1750s London became the home of many of Black people, Jews, Irish, Germans, and [[Huguenot]]s. In 1764 The Gentleman's Magazine reported that there was 'supposed to be near 20,000 Negroe servants'  -Evidence of the number of black residents in London has been found through registered burials. The people of London had widespread views that Black people in London were less than human;  {{Citation needed|date=January 2011}} these views were expressed in slave sale advertisements. Leading black activists of this era included [[Olaudah Equiano]], [[Ignatius Sancho]] and [[Quobna Ottobah Cugoano]].\nWith the support of other Britons these activists demanded that Blacks be freed from slavery.  Supporters involved in this movements included workers and other nationalities of the urban poor<!-- commented out because non-neutral point of view: who themselves suffered under the rule of the upper class -->. <!--commented out: was the slave trade widely carried on in Britain? Got a source for that?: that was widespread throughout Britain -->.  At this time the slavery of whites was forbidden, but the legal statuses of these practices were not clearly defined.  Free black slaves could not be enslaved, but blacks who were brought as slaves to Britain were considered the property of their owners.\nDuring this era [[Lord Mansfield]] declared that a slave who fled from his master could not be taken by force or sold abroad, in the case of [[Somerset v Stewart]].  This verdict fuelled the numbers of Blacks that escaped slavery, and helped send slavery into decline.  In this same period many slave soldiers who fought on the side of the British in the [[American Revolutionary War]] arrived in London.  These soldiers were deprived of pensions and many of them became poverty-stricken and were reduced to begging on the streets.  The Blacks in London lived among the whites in areas of [[Mile End]], [[Stepney]], [[Paddington]] and [[St Giles, London|St Giles]]. The majority of these people did not live as slaves, but as servants to wealthy whites. Many became labeled as the \"Black Poor\" defined as former low wage soldiers, seafarers and plantation workers.<ref name=\"FilePower\">{{cite book|last=File|first=Nigel|first2=Chris|last2=Power|date=1981|title=Black Settlers in Britain 1555\u20131958|publisher=Heinnemann Educational|isbn=978-0435311735}}</ref>\n\nDuring the late 18th century there were many publications and memoirs written about the \"black poor\".  One example is the writings of Equiano, who became an unofficial spokesman for Britain\u2019s Black community.  A memoir about his life is entitled, ''[[The Interesting Narrative of the Life of Olaudah Equiano]]''. Equiano became a landowner in Cambridgeshire and married Susannah Cullen, from [[Soham]]. Both his daughters were born and baptised there.\n\nIn 1787 4,000 blacks were transported from London for resettlement to the colony of Sierra Leone with help from the Committee for the Relief of the Black Poor.<ref>http://www.betterworldbooks.com/african-americans-in-the-american-revolution-id-1155512723.aspx</ref>\n\n== 19th century ==\n\nComing into the early 19th century, more groups of black soldiers and seaman were displaced after the [[Napoleonic wars]] and some settled in London.  These settlers suffered and faced many challenges as did many black people in London.  <!-- (commented out: see [[Atlantic slave trade#Economics of slavery]] for debates about this.) In the late eighteenth century the slave trade declined, as a direct result of industrial [[capitalism]]{{citation needed|date=November 2010}} --><!-- there's debate about this, I've seen arguments that it was at its height just before abolition. Please provide evidence for your claim--> <!-- (commented out: there was only one parliament in Britain!): throughout this early period different parliaments throughout Britain followed suit and --> the slave trade was abolished completely in the British empire by 1834.  The number of blacks in London was steadily declining with these new laws.  Fewer blacks were brought into London from the West Indies and parts of Africa.<ref name=\"FilePower\" />\n\nDuring the mid-19th century there were restrictions on African immigration.  In the later part of the 19th century there was a buildup of small groups of black dockside communities in towns such as [[Canning Town]],<ref>Geoffrey Bell, ''The other Eastenders : Kamal Chunchie and West Ham's early black community'' (Stratford: Eastside Community Heritage, 2002)</ref> [[Liverpool]], and [[Cardiff]].  This was a direct effect of new shipping links that were established with the Caribbean and West Africa.\n\nDespite social prejudice and  racist discrimination in Victorian England, some nineteenth-century black people living in England achieved exceptional success. [[Pablo Fanque]], born poor as William Darby in Norwich, rose to become the proprietor of one of Britain's most successful Victorian circuses. He is immortalised in the lyrics of The Beatles song \"Being for the Benefit of Mr. Kite!\" Another famous black Briton was [[William Davidson (conspirator)|William Davison]], a conspirator executed in London for his role in the Cato Street Conspiracy against Lord Liverpool's government in 1820. Britain's first black [[High Sheriff]] was [[Nathaniel Wells]], the son of a slave from [[St Kitts]] and a slave trader. After his father's death he was freed and inherited a fortune. He moved to Monmouthshire's [[Piercefield House]] and became [[Sheriff of Monmouthshire]] in 1818. One of the leaders in 19th century [[chartism]] was [[William Cuffay]], who was born on a merchant ship in the West Indies in 1788, and whose father, had been a slave in St Kitts.<ref>{{cite web|publisher=BBC|work=History|title=William Cuffay (1788 - 1870)|url= http://www.bbc.co.uk/history/historic_figures/cuffay_william.shtml}}</ref>\n\n==20th century==\n\nOne of the black Londoners, [[Learie Constantine]], a cricketer from Trinidad and  welfare officer in the [[RAF]], was refused service at a London hotel. He stood up for his rights and later was awarded compensation.  That particular example is used by some to illustrate the slow change from racism towards acceptance and equality of all citizens in London.<ref>{{cite journal\n |title   = Race, empire and British wartime national identity, 1939\u201345\n |pages   = 220\u201337\n |first   = Sonya\n |last    = Rose\n |journal = Historical Research\n |volume  = 74\n |issue   = 184\n |date    = May 2001\n |doi     = 10.1111/1468-2281.00125\n|pmid = 18161216\n }}</ref>\n\n=== Post-war period ===\nIn 1950, it was estimated there  were no more than 20,000 non-White residents in the United Kingdom, mainly in England; almost all born overseas.<ref>{{Cite book|title=The Demographic Characteristics of Immigrant Populations|url= https://books.google.com/books?id=mmaRpUa1oSoC|publisher=Council of Europe Publishing|date=2002|isbn=9789287149749|language=en|editor-first=Werner|editor-last=Haug|editor-first2=Paul|editor-last2=Compton|editor-first3=Youssef|editor-last3=Courbage}}</ref> Just after the end of [[World War II]], the first groups of post-war Caribbean immigrants started to emigrate and settle in [[London]]. There were an estimated 492 that were passengers on the {{HMT|Empire Windrush}} that arrived at [[Tilbury Docks]] on 22 June 1948. These passengers settled in the area of [[Brixton]] which is now a prominently Black district in Britain. From the 1950s into the 1960s, there was a mass migration of workers from all over the English-speaking Caribbean, particularly [[Colony of Jamaica|Jamaica]]; who settled in the UK. These immigrants were invited to fill labour requirements in London\u2019s hospitals, transportation venues and railway development. There was a continuous influx of African students, sportsmen, and businessmen mixed within British society .<ref>{{Cite web|title = Black British timeline {{!}} Black London {{!}} Black British History|url = http://www.blackpresence.co.uk/black-british-timeline/|website = The Black Presence in Britain|access-date = 2016-02-14|language = en-GB}}</ref>  They are widely viewed as having been a major contributing factor to the rebuilding of the post-war urban London economy.\n\nIn 1962, the [[Commonwealth Immigrants Act 1962|Commonwealth Immigrants Act]] was passed in the UK along with a succession of other laws in [[Commonwealth Immigrants Act 1968|1968]], [[Immigration Act 1971|1971]], and [[British Nationality Act 1981|1981]] that severely restricted the entry of Black Caribbean immigrants into the United Kingdom. During this period, it is widely argued that emergent Blacks and Asians struggled in Britain against racism and prejudice. In 1975, a new voice emerged for the Black population of London; his name was [[David Pitt, Baron Pitt of Hampstead|David Pitt]] and he brought a new voice to the [[House of Lords]]. He spoke against racism and for equality in regards to all residents of Britain. At the [[1987 United Kingdom general election|1987 general election]], the first-ever [[Black British]] MPs were elected to the [[House of Commons]]; [[Diane Abbott]] for [[Hackney North and Stoke Newington (UK Parliament constituency)|Hackney North and Stoke Newington]], [[Bernie Grant]] for [[Tottenham (UK Parliament constituency)|Tottenham]] and [[Paul Boateng]] for [[Brent South (UK Parliament constituency)|Brent South]]. All were candidates from the [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]], and out of these three people; Abbott holds the distinction of being the first Black British woman to be elected to the House of Commons and is also the only one to still be an MP to the present day, as Grant died in 2000 and Boateng stood down in [[2005 United Kingdom general election|2005]].\n\nBy the end of the twentieth century, the number of Black Londoners numbered half a million, according to the [[United Kingdom Census 1991|1991 UK Census]]. An increasing number of these Black Londoners were London, or British-born. Even with this growing population and the first Blacks elected to the UK Parliament, many argue that there was still discrimination and a socio-economic imbalance in London among the Black community. In [[1992 United Kingdom general election|1992]], the number of Blacks in Parliament increased to six and in [[1997 United Kingdom general election|1997]], they increased their numbers to nine. There are still many problems that Black Londoners face; the new global and high-tech information revolution is changing the urban economy and some argue that it is driving unemployment rates among Blacks up relative to non-blacks,{{Citation needed|date=January 2008}} something which, it is argued, threatens to erode the progress made thus far.<ref name=\"FilePower\" />\n\nAs of June 2007, the Black population of London is 802,300, equivalent to 10.6% of the population of London. 4.3% of Londoners are Caribbean, 5.5% of Londoners are African and a further 0.8% are from other black backgrounds including American and Latin American. There are also 117,400 people who are mixed black and white.<ref>[http://www.neighbourhood.statistics.gov.uk/dissemination/LeadTableView.do?a=3&b=276743&c=london&d=13&e=13&g=325264&i=1001x1003x1004&m=0&r=1&s=1217082648365&enc=1&dsFamilyId=1809 Resident Population Estimates by Ethnic Group, All Persons]</ref> At the [[United Kingdom Census 2011|2011 UK Census]], the total Black population of London stood at 1,088,640 or 13.3% of the population.<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://www.ons.gov.uk/ons/rel/census/2011-census/key-statistics-for-local-authorities-in-england-and-wales/rft-table-ks201ew.xls|title = 2011 black population london|date = |access-date = |website = |publisher = |last = |first = }}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n{{Portal|London}}\n*[[Historical immigration to Great Britain]]\n*[[Black British]]\n*[[Ethnic groups in London]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n{{Black British topics}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Arrival Of Black Immigrants in London}}\n[[Category:Black British culture in London]]\n[[Category:Black British history]]\n[[Category:History of immigration to the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:History of London|African]]\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: \u2019s \u2192 's (3)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/History_of_African_presence_in_London"}
{"title_page": "SWAYAM", "text_new": "'''[https://swayam.gov.in/ SWAYAM]''' is a Hindi acronym stands for \"'''Study Webs of Active-Learning for Young Aspiring Minds'''\" is an Indian [[Massive open online course]] (MOOC) platform. SWAYAM is an initiative launched by [[Ministry of Human Resource Development|the Ministry of Human Resource Development]], [[Government of India]] under [[Digital India]] to give a coordinated stage and free entry to web courses, covering all advanced education, High School and skill sector courses.It was launched on 9th July 2017 by [[President of India|Honorable President of India]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/home/education/news/mhrds-swayam-programme-aims-to-make-study-material-available-to-all/articleshow/67955817.cms|title=MHRD's SWAYAM programme aims to make study material available to all - Times of India|website=The Times of India|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Krishna|first=V.V.|last2=Chandra|first2=Nimesh|title=Knowledge Production and Knowledge Transfer: A Study of Two Indian Institutes of Technology (IIT Madras and IIT Bombay)|url=http://dx.doi.org/10.4337/9780857938008.00014|journal=Academic Entrepreneurship in Asia|doi=10.4337/9780857938008.00014}}</ref><ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://swayam.gov.in/about|title=SWAYAM|date=2020-03-29|website=SWAYAM|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nSWAYAM has been developed cooperatively by MHRD (Ministry of Human Resource Development) and AICTE (All India Council for Technical Education) with the help of Microsoft and is equipped for facilitating 2,000 courses. The platform offers free access to everyone and hosts courses from class 9 till post-graduation. It enables professors and faculty of centrally funded institutes like [[Indian Institutes of Technology|IITs]], [[Indian Institutes of Management|IIMs]], [[Indian Institutes of Science Education and Research|IISERs]], etc. to teach students.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://pib.gov.in/newsite/PrintRelease.aspx?relid=109585|title=Highlights of the Achievements of the Union HRD Ministry|website=pib.gov.in|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.alkhateebgroup.org/mook.asp|title=Alkhateeb Polytechnic|website=www.alkhateebgroup.org|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref> \u00a0\n\nAs per the official website, there are 203 partnering institutes, 2748 completed courses, 12541992 student enrollment, 915538 exam registrations, and 654664 successful certificates.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://swayam.gov.in/nc_details/|title=Details|date=2020-03-29|website=SWAYAM|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n== '''<big>Functionality</big>''' ==\nSWAYAM operates MOOCs  learning resources in different ways and structure. Learning in SWAYAM has four parts/quadrants: [https://www.bristol.ac.uk/esu/media/tutorials/design-principles/page_02.htm e-Tutorial], [https://www.lexico.com/en/definition/e-content e-Content], Discussion forum, [https://www.lexico.com/en/definition/assessment Assessment].<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite journal|last=Samanta|first=Anuva|date=2018-07-05|title=Analytical Study of SWAYAM|url=http://ijrar.com/upload_issue/ijrar_issue_1471.pdf|journal=Analytical Study of SWAYAM|pages=6|via=Google Scholar}}</ref>\n\nThe first quadrant is direct teaching means not much of extra work by students, it could include teaching video, [[animation]], [[Microsoft PowerPoint|PowerPoint presentation]], [[Podcast]] and so on. All these depend on what the subject is and what the strategy adopted by the teacher to teach the students.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref>{{Cite journal|date=2016-11-30|title=THE JOURNEY OF SWAYAM: INDIA MOOCS INITIATIVE|url=http://oasis.col.org/bitstream/handle/11599/2592/PDF?sequence=1&isAllowed=y|journal=Journey of swayam|volume=|pages=10|via=Google scholar}}</ref>\n\nThe second quadrant is an e-content which could include e-books, [https://www.lexico.com/en/definition/illustration illustrations], [[Case study|Case studies]], [[Open content|Open source content]], Reference link, further reading sources and so on.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Bast|first=Dr.Felix|date=2019-07-03|title=SWAYAM MOOC education on go|url=http://nopr.niscair.res.in/bitstream/123456789/48955/1/SR%2056%287%29%2031-33.pdf|journal=education on go|volume=|pages=3|via=Google scholar}}</ref>\n\nThe third quadrant is about clearing student's queries. [[Internet forum|Discussion forum]] is a part of it means students can interact with other students and faculty to clarify their doubts. The discussion forum is like a doubt counter where any student or faculty can answer the question of a student.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nThe fourth quadrant is self-assessment to check what a student have studied and whether he/she is eligible to get certificate. It could be tests in the form of [[Multiple choice|Multiple Choice Questions]] (MCQs), or quiz or s hort answer questions, long answer questions, etc. The fourth quadrant also has Frequently Asked Question (FAQs) and their answers to clarify common misconceptions among students.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n== '''<big>National Coordinators</big>''' ==\nNine national coordinators are appointed to ensure and maintain good quality content. Each coordinator has assigned a particular area for maintenance.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n1.\u00a0 \u00a0 \u00a0[[All India Council for Technical Education]] (AICTE) has been appointed National coordinator by [[Ministry of Human Resource Development|MHRD]] for self-paced and international courses.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://swayam.gov.in/nc_details/AICTE|title=Swayam Central|website=swayam.gov.in|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref> \n\n2.\u00a0 \u00a0 \u00a0[[Nptel|National Programme on Technology Enhanced Learning]] (NPTEL) has been appointed National coordinator by [[Ministry of Human Resource Development|MHRD]] for engineering sector courses.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://swayam.gov.in/nc_details/NPTEL|title=Swayam Central|website=swayam.gov.in|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref>\n\n3.\u00a0 \u00a0 \u00a0[[University Grants Commission (India)|University Grants Permission]] (UGC) has been appointed National coordinator by [[Ministry of Human Resource Development|MHRD]] for non-technical post-graduate education.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://swayam.gov.in/nc_details/UGC|title=Swayam Central|website=swayam.gov.in|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref>\n\n4.\u00a0 \u00a0 \u00a0[http://cec.nic.in/cec/ Consortium for Educational Communication] (CEC) has been appointed National coordinator by [[Ministry of Human Resource Development|MHRD]] for undergraduate education.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://swayam.gov.in/nc_details/CEC|title=Swayam Central|website=swayam.gov.in|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref>\n\n5.\u00a0 \u00a0 \u00a0[[National Council of Educational Research and Training]] (NCERT) has been appointed National coordinator by [[Ministry of Human Resource Development|MHRD]] for school education.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://swayam.gov.in/nc_details/NCERT|title=Swayam Central|website=swayam.gov.in|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref>\n\n6.\u00a0 \u00a0 \u00a0[[National Institute of Open Schooling]] (NIOS) has been appointed National coordinator by [[Ministry of Human Resource Development|MHRD]] for school education.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://swayam.gov.in/nc_details/NIOS|title=Swayam Central|website=swayam.gov.in|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref>\n\n7.\u00a0 \u00a0 \u00a0[[National Institute of Open Schooling|Indira Gandhi National Open University]] (IGNOU) has been appointed National coordinator by [[Ministry of Human Resource Development|MHRD]] for out-of-school students.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://swayam.gov.in/nc_details/IGNOU|title=Swayam Central|website=swayam.gov.in|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref>\n\n8.\u00a0 \u00a0 \u00a0[[Indian Institute of Management Bangalore|Indian Institute of Management, Bangalore]] (IIMB) has been appointed National coordinator by [[Ministry of Human Resource Development|MHRD]] for management studies.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://swayam.gov.in/nc_details/IIMB|title=Swayam Central|website=swayam.gov.in|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref>\n\n9.\u00a0 \u00a0 \u00a0[[Indian Institute of Management Bangalore|National Institute of Technical Teachers Training and Research]] (NITTTR) has been appointed National coordinator by [[Ministry of Human Resource Development|MHRD]] for Teacher training program.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://swayam.gov.in/nc_details/NITTTR|title=Swayam Central|website=swayam.gov.in|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref>\n<br />\n\n== <big>'''Courses offered'''</big> ==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|Subject\n|No. of courses\n|Offered by/under\n|}\n<br />\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n| colspan=\"3\" |SCHOOL\n|-\n|Accountary\n|1\n|NCERT\n|-\n|Biology\n|3\n|NCERT\n|-\n|Business studies\n|1\n|NCERT\n|-\n|Chemistry\n|3\n|NCERT\n|-\n|Economics\n|2\n|NCERT\n|-\n|Food Nutrition for Healthy Living\n|1\n|NCERT\n|-\n|Geography\n|2\n|NCERT\n|-\n|Mathematics\n|3\n|NCERT\n|-\n|Physics\n|4\n|NCERT\n|-\n|Psychology\n|2\n|NCERT\n|-\n|Sociology\n|2\n|NCERT\n|}\n<br />\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n| colspan=\"3\" |Undergraduate courses\n|-\n| colspan=\"3\" |Engineering\n|-\n|Aerospace\n|1\n|<nowiki>- IIT Madras</nowiki>\n|-\n|Bioengineering\n|3\n|<nowiki>- IIT Madras</nowiki>\n|-\n|Biotechnology\n|1\n|<nowiki>- IIT Madras</nowiki>\n|-\n|Chemical\n|1\n|<nowiki>- IIT Madras</nowiki>\n|-\n|Civil\n|1\n|<nowiki>- IIT Madras</nowiki>\n|-\n|\n\n\n\n\nComputer Science\n|18\n|<nowiki>- Punjabi University</nowiki>\n\n- Panjab University\n\n- Anna University\n\n- Gujarat University\n\n- IIT Madras\n\n- IGNOU\n|-\n|Electrical\n|4\n|<nowiki>- IIT Madras</nowiki>\n|-\n|\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\nElectronics\n|115\n|<nowiki>- IIT Madras</nowiki>\n\n- Anna University\n\n- IIT Mumbai\n\n- IIT Kanpur\n\n- IIT Roorkee\n\n- IIT Kharagpur\n\n- IISc\n\n- IIT Delhi\n\n- IIT Guwahati\n\n- IISER Kolkata\n\n- IIIT Delhi\n|-\n|Environment\n|1\n|<nowiki>- Devi Ahilya Vishwavidyalaya</nowiki>\n|-\n|\n\n\n\nGeneral\n|31\n|<nowik