arch\n|1\n|<nowiki>- University of Hyderabad</nowiki>\n|}\nAnd also have post-graduate courses.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://swayam.gov.in/explorer|title=Swayam|website=swayam.gov.in|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref>\n\n== '''<big>Credit Transfer</big>''' ==\nAll the courses offered by SWAYAM are credible and are recognized by the government of India. All the courses are valid in the country and also, [[University Grants Commission (India)|UGC]] has announced a \u201cCredit Framework for Online Learning Courses through SWAYAM\u201d Regulations, 2016 in the Gazette of India on July 19, 2016 where credit transfer for SWAYAM courses is defined. The UGC regulation requires Universities to make changes in their rules and regulation to incorporate provision for credit mobility and MOOC courses under the SWAYAM platform. The certificates of degrees and diploma will be given on clearing the criteria of course taken and that certificate will be a credit mobility for academic credits<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://storage.googleapis.com/swayam1-pub-data/UGC-(Credit-Framework-for-Online-Learning-Courses-through-SWAYAM)-Regulation%2C-2016.pdf|title=Credit Framework for Online Learning Courses through SWAYAM)|date=2016-07-19|work=The Gazette of India|access-date=2020-03-29|url-status=live}}</ref>. The current guideline of UGC constrains just 20 percent of the courses for a degree-level program.\n\n== '''<big>Local Chapter</big>''' ==\n[[Nptel|NPTEL]] is a joint initiative of the [[Indian Institutes of Technology|IITs]] and [[Indian Institute of Science|IISC]], NPTEL offers online courses and certification in various fields.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://nptelindia.wordpress.com/|title=NPTEL - A Joint Initiative of IITs and IISc, Bengaluru|website=NPTEL - A Joint Initiative of IITs and IISc, Bengaluru|language=en|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref> NPTEL has set up a system to provide certificate courses in different colleges all over India termed as [https://nptel.ac.in/LocalChapter/about_LocalChapter.html NPTEL- local chapters]. A local chapter will be under one faculty member of the college- one single contact and so called [[Point of contact|Single Point of Contact]] (SPOC).\n\nFurther under the [https://nptel.ac.in/LocalChapter/index.html SWAYAM-NPTEL] webpage, two more departments are operated, i.e. '''[https://nptel.ac.in/LocalChapter/nptelnews.html NPTEL news]''' and '''[https://nptel.ac.in/LocalChapter/newsfromlc.html SWAYAM-NPTEL Local chapter news]'''. NPTEL news highlights bulletins about SPOC timeline, list of active local chapters, local chapter\u2019s ratings, etc. And other department shows news from local chapters i.e. local chapter colleges/universities.\n\n== '''<big>SWAYAM PRABHA</big>''' ==\n'''[https://www.swayamprabha.gov.in/ SWAYAM PRABHA]''' is an education learning platform initiated by [[Ministry of Human Resource Development|the Ministry of Human Resource Development]] (MHRD) available [[24/7 service|24x7]] through 32 [[Direct-to-home television in India|DTH channels]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://swayamprabha.gov.in/|title=Swayam Prabha {{!}} Free 32 DTH channels|website=swayamprabha.gov.in|language=en|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref> This initiative provide an educational program on Television on multiple time zone. The content provider is NPTEL, IITs, UGC, NCERT, etc. same as of SWAYAM online portal.\n\n\u00a0\n\n\u00a0\n\n\n\u00a0 \u00a0 \u00a0 \u00a0 \u00a0 \u00a0 \u00a0 \u00a0 \n\n\u00a0 \u00a0\n<references />\n[[Category:Ministry of Human Resource Development (India)]]\n", "name_user": "MrPatel383001", "label": "safe", "comment": "just written reference heading", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/SWAYAM"}
{"title_page": "History of African Americans in Utah", "text_new": "[[File:Mia Love official portrait.jpg|thumb|Mia Love, first African American Congresswoman from Utah]]\nThe first [[African Americans]] to arrive in [[Utah]] were [[North American fur trade|fur trappers]] in the early [[19th century]]. The second influx consisted of both [[Freedman|freedmen]] who were converts to [[The Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints]] and slaves belonging to [[White people|white]] converts. Later, most African American immigrants to Utah would migrate out for labor-related motivations. African Americans have traditionally been composed only a small part of the total population in Utah, with the [[2010 United States Census|2010 census]] placing the percentage of African Americans at 1.06%. Utah ranks 40th in the United States for [[List of U.S. states and territories by African-American population|total African American population]] and 43rd in percentage of residents who are African American.\n\n== Fur trapping and exploration period (early 1800s to 1847) ==\n[[File:Beckwourth citizen.jpg|thumb|James P. Beckwourth, fur trapper]]\nThe only record of African American presence in Utah prior to the arrival of [[Mormon pioneers|pioneers]] from The Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints was in the case of a few fur-trappers that traveled to the [[Utah Territory|Utah territory]]. [[James Beckwourth|James P. Beckwourth]] was a member of [[William Henry Ashley|William Ashley]]\u2019s [[Rocky Mountain Fur Company]], and spent several years off and on in Utah, especially in [[Cache Valley]] in the mid-1820\u2019s.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Jim Beckwourth: Black Mountain Man and War Chief of the Crows|last=Wilson|first=Elinor|publisher=University of Oklahoma Press|year=1972|isbn=978-0-8061-1012-7|location=Norman, Oklahoma, USA|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/jimbeckwourthbla0000wils}}</ref><ref name=\":2\">{{Cite book|title=A History of Blacks in Utah, 1825-1910|last=Coleman|first=Ronald Gerald|publisher=The University of Utah|year=1980|isbn=|location=Salt Lake City, Utah, USA|pages=26\u201330}}</ref>\n\n[[Jedediah Smith]] led several expeditions in the late 1820\u2019s to the Utah territory that involved African Americans Petre Ranne and Polette Labross.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\nIn 1843, on [[John C. Fr\u00e9mont|John C. Fremont]]\u2019s second westward expedition (which included the Utah territory), a young free African American named Jacob Dodson accompanied him.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\n== Utah slavery and arrival of Latter-day Saint pioneers (1847-1862) ==\n{{See also|History of slavery in Utah|Mormon pioneers}}\nOn July 22, 1847, pioneers from [[The Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints]], led by [[Brigham Young]], entered the Salt Lake Valley, fleeing [[Missouri]] and [[Illinois]] due to intense persecution. By the end of 1847, there were 12 African Americans living in the Salt Lake Valley, among them 8 slaves (including Oscar Crosby and Hark Lay), and a family of four free African Americans (Isaac and [[Jane Manning James]] family). [[Green Flake]], who had also arrived with the initial pioneer company, had gone with a group of pioneers to help others traveling across the plains.<ref name=\":2\" />[[File:Jane Elizabeth Manning James.jpg|thumb|Jane Elizabeth Manning James, free African American and early Utah pioneer]]By 1848 there were approximately 50 African Americans living in the Utah Territory after another pioneer company had arrived. 24 were slaves who had traveled from [[Mississippi]] led by [[John Brown (Mormon pioneer)|John Brown]], and they were joined by 12 other African Americans, mostly slaves, when they passed through [[Winter Quarters (North Omaha, Nebraska)|Winter Quarters]] in [[Nebraska]].<ref name=\":2\" />\n\nIn the 1850 US census, there were 50 \"colored\" people living in the Utah Territory, constituting 0.4% of the total territorial population.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.socialexplorer.com/tables/Census1850/R11872748|title=United States Census, 1850|last=|first=|date=|website=www.socialexplorer.com|language=en|access-date=2018-11-11}}</ref>\n\nIn the [[Compromise of 1850]], Utah was established as a [[Slave states and free states|slavery territory]], officially legalizing slavery in the Utah territory.\n\nIn 1852, the Utah Legislature, with input from the [[President of the Church|prophet]] and territorial governor Brigham Young, established the [[Act in Relation to Service]], which established a legal precedent for slavery in the territory (both for African Americans and [[Native Americans in the United States|Native Americans]]).<ref name=\":2\" /> These laws both protected the rights and proper treatment of the slaves while also legitimizing slavery and the slaves' duty to their masters. For example, it required that slaves be protected from unwilling transfer and sexual exploitation and be given proper treatment and schooling. On the other hand, slaves were required to submit dutifully to their masters' wishes and to punishment when necessary.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://blackpast.org/primarywest/utah-slave-code-1852|title=The Utah Territory Slave Code (1852) {{!}} The Black Past: Remembered and Reclaimed|website=blackpast.org|language=en|access-date=2018-11-11}}</ref>\n\nUnder Utah territorial law (before the [[Reconstruction Amendments]] were passed), African Americans could not [[Voting|vote]], serve on [[Jury|juries]], be elected to the legislature, or serve in the militia.<ref>{{Cite book|title=A Union, Utah, History|last=Madsen|first=Steven K.|publisher=Sons of Utah Pioneers|year=1981|isbn=|location=Utah|pages=}}</ref>\n\nOn June 19, 1862, the US Congress abolished slavery in Utah and all other US territories.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.freedmen.umd.edu/freeterr.htm|title=Emancipation in the Federal Territories, June 19, 1862|last=|first=|date=|website=www.freedmen.umd.edu|access-date=2018-11-13}}</ref>\n\n== Post-slavery period (1862-1950) ==\n{{See also|Racial segregation in the United States}}\n\n=== Population and distribution ===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+'''Census Data for African American Population in Utah from 1860 to 1950'''<ref name=\":6\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.socialexplorer.com/a9676d974c/explore|title=US Demography 1790 to Present|website=Social Explorer|language=en|access-date=2018-11-16}}</ref><ref name=\":4\">{{Cite web|url=http://gardner.utah.edu/bebr/Documents/studies/Utah_Minorities.pdf|title=Utah Minorities: The Story Told by 150 Years of Census Data|last=Perlich|first=Pamela S|last2=Eccles|first2=Davis S.|date=October 2002|website=University of Utah|access-date=}}</ref>\n!Year\n!Total Population\n!African American Population\n!Percentage of Population\n|-\n|1860\n|40,273\n|59\n|0.15%\n|-\n|1870\n|86,786\n|118\n|0.14%\n|-\n|1880\n|143,963\n|232\n|0.16%\n|-\n|1890\n|207,905\n|588\n|0.28%\n|-\n|1900\n|276,749\n|672\n|0.25%\n|-\n|1910\n|373,351\n|1,144\n|0.31%\n|-\n|1920\n|449,396\n|1,446\n|0.32%\n|-\n|1930\n|507,847\n|1,108\n|0.22%\n|-\n|1940\n|550,310\n|1,235\n|0.22%\n|-\n|1950\n|676,909\n|2,729\n|0.40%\n|}\nAs shown in the table above, the historic population of African Americans in Utah has been proportionally low.<ref name=\":4\" /> During the late 1800s, the greatest population of African Americans was in [[Salt Lake City]], followed by [[Uintah County, Utah|Uintah County]] due to the military presence, and [[Weber County, Utah|Weber County]] due to the railroad center located in [[Ogden, Utah|Ogden]].<ref name=\":2\" /> Unlike other western African American populations in the time period where single African American men was the norm, African American Utahns in the late 19th and early 20th centuries were mostly organized into family units.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\nUntil about 1870, most of the African American immigration to Utah was composed of converts to The Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints. After 1870, the majority of African American immigrants were immigrating for non-religious reasons.<ref name=\":2\" /> Despite this growth, the proportion of African Americans in Utah remained consistently low. One major reason for this trend was the [[Black people and Mormonism|lack of full acceptance of African Americans in the Latter-day Saint church]] (which lasted until [[1978 Revelation on Priesthood|1978]]), which resulted in a low incentive for African American converts and minimal [[Missionary (LDS Church)|missionary effort]] focused on [[Africa]]n countries.\n\n=== Industry ===\nThe [[United States Armed Forces|United States Military]] and the arrival of the railroads in Utah were perhaps the two biggest pull factors and employers for African Americans in this time period. In 1900, the most common occupation for African Americans was soldier, and second was \"servants and waiters\", which included the large number who worked for railroad companies. Agriculture and mining were also common occupations at the time.<ref name=\":2\" />\n[[File:Trinity AME Church SLC.jpeg|thumb|Trinity A.M.E. church in Salt Lake City]]\n\n=== African American community ===\nAs the African American community grew with the insurgence of non-religious motivated pioneers in the late 1800s, and especially grouped in places like Salt Lake City and Ogden, African American media, organizations, and churches (not The Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints) began to emerge in greater numbers. Between 1890 and 1891, the [[Trinity A.M.E. Church|first African Methodist Episcopal church]] in Utah was established in Salt Lake and became a focal point for the local African American community.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://npgallery.nps.gov/NRHP/GetAsset/NRHP/76001831_text|title=National Register of Historic Places Registration Form: Trinity African Methodist Episcopal Church|last=Smith|first=John S. H.|last2=Roberts|first2=Allen D.|date=June 11, 1976|website=National Park Service|access-date=November 27, 2018}}</ref> In the 1890s and early 1900s an African American [[Baptists|Baptist]] church was established in Salt Lake.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\n=== African American military units ===\n{{See also|Military history of African Americans}}\nThere were two notable segregated African American military units in Utah in the late 1800s: the [[9th Cavalry Regiment (United States)|Ninth Cavalry Regiment]] and the [[24th Infantry Regiment (United States)|24th Infantry Regiment]], stationed in [[Fort Duchesne, Utah|Fort Duchesne]] (Uintah County) and Salt Lake City respectively.<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite book|title=The Story of the Negro Pioneer|last=Carter|first=Kate B.|publisher=Daughters of Utah Pioneers|year=1865|isbn=|location=|pages=}}</ref> They were sent initially to help in the [[American Indian Wars|Indian Wars]] and in other necessary capacities. These two units composed a sizable portion of the African American population of Utah in this time period, notably giving Uintah county the second largest population of African Americans for a period of time.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\nFort Duchesne was reportedly segregated, but soldier-to-soldier interactions were generally not separated by race.<ref name=\":5\" />\n\n=== Discrimination/segregation ===\nThe Utah Legislature passed an [[Anti-miscegenation laws in the United States|anti-miscegenation law]] in 1888 which prohibited marriage \"between a negro and a white person\".<ref>{{Cite book|title=Compiled Laws of Utah, Volume II|last=|first=|publisher=Herbert Pembroke|year=1888|isbn=|location=Salt Lake City|pages=}}</ref>\n\nSome of the segregation present in Utah emerged in the late 1890s as a direct result of the arrival of the 24th Infantry to Salt Lake. Shop owners were reportedly concerned about African American soldiers entering their shops and restaurants, and were prompted to put up signs expressing their racial preferences.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\nUtah Schools were not formally segregated.<ref name=\":2\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://historytogo.utah.gov/utah_chapters/utah_today/thecivilrightsmovementinutah.html|title=The Civil Rights Movement in Utah|website=historytogo.utah.gov|access-date=2018-11-27}}</ref>\n\n== Desegregation and the civil rights movement (1950-1978) ==\n{{See also|Civil rights movement}}\n[[File:Salt lake city hotel utah 1925.jpg|thumb|Hotel Utah, Salt Lake City, circa 1925]]\nThe early 1950s brought much-anticipated change to the Utah community of African Americans. Previously, many famous African Americans, including the opera singer Maria Anderson and other prominent musicians such as [[Paul Robeson]], [[Harry Belafonte]], [[Ella Fitzgerald]], and [[Lionel Hampton]], all faced discrimination as they visited Utah. The [[Joseph Smith Memorial Building|Hotel Utah]] required them to abstain from eating at the hotel restaurant and to use the freight elevator.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.utahhumanities.org/stories/items/show/228|title=The Great White Palace: African American Segregation in Utah|last=Andersen|first=Rebecca|date=2012|website=|access-date=7 November 2018}}</ref> Others were unable to find accommodation in the hotels.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=https://heritage.utah.gov/history/uhg-civil-rights-movement-utah|title=The Civil Rights Movement in Utah - Utah Department of Heritage and Arts|date=2016-04-26|work=Utah Department of Heritage and Arts|access-date=2018-11-07|language=en-US}}</ref> Multiple governmental authorities, including the [[Ambassador to the United Nations|American Ambassador to the United Nations]], [[Ralph Bunche]], and Congressman [[Adam Clayton Powell Jr.|Adam Clayton Powell]], were also rejected by the hotel, forcing them to seek lodging in private homes.<ref name=\":1\" /> Bars, night clubs, and many dining establishments in Salt Lake City refused service to African Americans.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite journal|last=Peterson|first=F. Ross|date=Winter 2005|title=\"Blindside\": Utah on the Eve of Brown v. Board of Education|url=http://utahhistory.sdlhost.com/#/item/000000033000075/view|journal=Utah Historical Quarterly|volume=73|pages=4\u201320|via=}}</ref> The practice of segregation quickly began to dissolve, with public attractions such as [[Lagoon (amusement park)|Lagoon]], an amusement park in [[Farmington, Utah|Farmington]], allowing African Americans entry and use of the swimming pool and other park facilities.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\":0\" />\n\nOn the brink of ''[[Brown v. Board of Education]],'' Utah schools and universities tended to avoid hiring African American teachers, tending to favor whites for such positions.<ref name=\":1\" /> According to the [[NAACP]], no African American had taught in the Utah education system until late 1954, when the first black public school teacher was hired.<ref name=\":1\" /> Continued segregation existed not only in educational positions, but also in college sports until 1953, when the first black football players were accepted onto the [[Utah State University|Utah State Agricultural College]] football team.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nBy 1960, the African American population in Utah had grown by more than 50%, with census data showing an overall African American population of 4,148 people, comprising 0.47% of Utah's total population.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.socialexplorer.com|title=United States Census, 1960|last=|first=|date=|website=Social Explorer|access-date=6 November 2018}}</ref> In 1963, Utah's 75-year ban on miscegenation was lifted, allowing interracial marriage. Utah was the second-to-last state to repeal its anti-miscegenation statute, with [[Wyoming]] repealing in 1965.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Mason|first=Patrick Q|date=Spring 2008|title=The Prohibition of Interracial Marriage in Utah, 1888-1963|url=http://utahhistory.sdlhost.com/#/item/000000033000161/view|journal=Utah Historical Quarterly|volume=76|pages=108\u2013131|via=}}</ref>\n[[File:Spencer W. Kimball3.JPG|thumb|220x220px|Spencer W. Kimball]]\nA 1967 ''[[Daily Utah Chronicle]]'' interview with several African Americans in northern Utah provided insight into African-American views of racism and Utah's integration of civil rights policies. The interview reveals the African Americans, particularly youth, felt continued discouragement of interracial marriage, even after legalization, was wrong and unnecessary. Youth at [[West High School (Utah)|West High School]] reported that they felt welcome and received fair treatment at school. Students at [[Ogden High School]], however, complained about unfairness and prejudice from some teachers and principals. One woman felt offended at a realtor for not allowing her to look at house listings in predominantly white, middle-class East Salt Lake, taking her instead to the poor, dilapidated houses in West Salt Lake.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com|title=Negro Residents Enjoy Beehive State|last=Scott|first=Ron|date=25 Oct 1967|work=The Broad Axe|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nBy 1970, the African-American population in Utah had grown to 6,324.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.socialexplorer.com|title=United States Census, 1970|last=|first=|date=|website=Social Explorer|access-date=6 November 2018}}</ref> The Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints continued withholding priesthood authority from African Americans, causing tension and criticism within the church. [[David O. McKay]], President of the Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints, issued a letter to people struggling with confusion over the doctrine surrounding African Americans, stating resolutely that the time would come when African Americans would be given full rights in the church.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Mormonism and the Negro: an Explanation and Defense of the Doctrine of the Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-Day Saints in Regard to Negroes and Others of Negroid Blood|last=Stewart|first=John J.|publisher=Horizon|year=1978|isbn=|location=|pages=}}</ref>\n\nIn June 1978, [[Spencer W. Kimball]], then-president of The Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints issued [[1978 Revelation on Priesthood|Official Declaration 2]], which affirmed the Church's belief in the equality of all men and ended the long-standing practice of withholding certain church privileges from African American members, such as holding the priesthood and entering [[Temple (LDS Church)|temples]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.churchofjesuschrist.org/study/scriptures/dc-testament/od/2?lang=eng|title=Official Declaration 2|last=|first=|date=September 1978|website=The Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-Day Saints|access-date=7 November 2018}}</ref>\n\n== Modern day African-Americans (1978-today) ==\n=== Population ===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+Census Data for African American Population in Utah, 1980-2010<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.socialexplorer.com|title=United States Census, 1980|last=|first=|date=|website=Social Explorer|access-date=6 November 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.socialexplorer.com|title=United States Census, 1990|last=|first=|date=|website=Social Explorer|access-date=6 November 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.socialexplorer.com|title=United States Census, 2000|last=|first=|date=|website=Social Explorer|access-date=6 November 2018}}</ref><ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.socialexplorer.com|title=United States Census, 2010|last=|first=|date=|website=Social Explorer|access-date=6 November 2018}}</ref>\n!Year\n!Total Population\n!African American Population\n!Percentage of Population\n|-\n|1980\n|1,461,037\n|9,225\n|0.63%\n|-\n|1990\n|1,722,850\n|11,576\n|0.67%\n|-\n|2000\n|2,233,169\n|17,657\n|0.79%\n|-\n|2010\n|2,763,885\n|29,287\n|1.06%\n|}\nAfrican American population in Utah continued increasing at an accelerating rate, reaching just over 1% of the overall population during the 2010 census.<ref name=\":3\" />\n[[File:Lipofsky-Karl-Malone-32727.jpg|thumb|Karl Malone]]\n\n=== Sports ===\nUtah's college and professional sports scene includes hundreds of African American athletes, many of which receive great support from fans around the state. The roster for the [[Utah Jazz]], an [[National Basketball Association|NBA]] franchise based in Salt Lake City, has recruited well-known African American players such as [[Karl Malone]], [[Paul Millsap]], [[Donovan Mitchell]], [[Al Jefferson]], and [[Derrick Favors]], among many [[Utah Jazz all-time roster|others]].\n\nRacism still serves as a form of denigration during sports rivalries in Utah. An interview with an African American basketball player at the University of Utah revealed that [[racial slurs]] are still commonly shouted out during and after sports matches. Attempts of [[Violence|physical violence]] after games were also reported by the student.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://dailyutahchronicle.com/2018/02/12/black-athletes-struggles-outrun-racism/|title=Black Athletes' Struggles to Outrun Racism|last=Meservy|first=Brittni|date=February 12, 2018|work=Daily Utah Chronicle|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n=== Religion ===\nA 2009 Pew Forum study showed that approximately 3% of members of the Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints, the predominant religion in Utah, were African American.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.pewforum.org/2009/07/24/a-portrait-of-mormons-in-the-us/|title=A Portrait of Mormons in the U.S.|last=Pew Forum|date=2009-07-24|website=Pew Forum|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nThe Calvary Baptist Church, a well-known African American house of worship, has had a presence in Salt Lake City since 1898. Founded by a small group of African American women who gathered regularly to pray, the small group quickly expanded and moved from personal homes into a larger building. Reverend A. E. Reynolds was invited to act as the Calvary Baptist Church's first pastor and served for approximately three years. Membership continued to grow rapidly. Under the direction of Reverend France Davis, a new facility was constructed in 2001 for worship services. Each Sunday, around 300 African Americans gather at the Calvary Baptist Church to receive a free breakfast and hear Reverend Davis preach a sermon.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://calvaryslc.com/our-history/|title=Our History - Calvary Baptist Church|last=Calvary Baptist Church|date=2017-04-11|website=Calvary Baptist Church|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n=== Modern racial issues ===\nA 2013 study shows a large racial divide between East Salt Lake City and West Salt Lake City. The east is more affluent and is home to few African Americans and other minorities. The west, home to a much greater proportion of African Americans and other minorities, is a much more dilapidated, poverty-stricken area, with a 17.1% poverty rate according to the federally defined poverty line.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://ucdp.utah.edu/reports/HUD_Portal/FHEA/Salt_Lake_County/RCAPMarch2013.pdf|title=Racially Concentrated Areas of Poverty (RCAP) and Ethnically Concentrated Areas of Poverty (ECAP)|last=|first=|date=2013|website=Salt Lake Tribune|access-date=7 November 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe Salt Lake City chapter of the [[National Association for the Advancement of Colored People|National Association for the Advancement of Colored People (NAACP)]] claimed in 2017 to receive over 10 reports of racism weekly. Complaints include workplace unfairness, use of racial slurs, and threats of violence. Reports of racism are steadily increasing in the state.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thespectrum.com/story/news/2018/01/30/racism-workplace-social-media-inside-schools-utah/905356001/|title=Racism in Utah: In the workplace, on social media, and inside schools'|last=Havens|first=Emily|date=January 30, 2018|website=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n== Notable residents ==\n[[File:Al Jackson (42359850450).jpg|thumb|Alvin B. Jackson, Former Utah State Senator]]\n\n*[[James Beckwourth]]- fur trader and explorer\n*[[Green Flake]]- pioneer\n*[[Jane Manning James]]- pioneer\n*[[Elijah Abel]]- carpenter and church leader\n*[[Joseph Freeman (Mormon)|Joseph Freeman]]- first African American to receive the [[Priesthood (Latter Day Saints)|priesthood]] after the 1978 announcement by Spencer W. Kimball\n*[[Black Mormons#Wynetta Willis Martin|Wynetta Willis Martin]]- singer and [[Brigham Young University|BYU]] faculty member\n*[[Thurl Bailey]]- NBA basketball player\n*[[Byron Scott]]- NBA basketball coach and player\n*[[Alex Boy\u00e9]]- singer and actor\n*[[Alvin B. Jackson]]- state senator\n*[[Frank Jackson (basketball)|Frank Jackson]]- basketball player\n*[[Bryan Kehl]]- [[National Football League|NFL]] football player\n*[[Karl Malone]]- NBA basketball player\n*[[Mia Love]]- US congresswoman\n\n== See also ==\n{{Portal|United States|Utah}}\n*[[Black people and Mormonism]]\n*[[Black Mormons]]\n*[[History of Utah]]\n*[[National and ethnic cultures of Utah]]\n\n== References ==\n<references />\n\n{{African American topics}}\n\n[[Category:Ethnic groups in Utah]]\n[[Category:African-American cultural history]]\n[[Category:History of Utah]]\n[[Category:African diaspora history]]\n", "text_old": "[[File:Mia Love official portrait.jpg|thumb|Mia Love, first African American Congresswoman from Utah]]\nThe first [[African Americans]] to arrive in [[Utah]] were [[North American fur trade|fur trappers]] in the early [[19th century]]. The second influx consisted of both [[Freedman|freedmen]] who were converts to [[The Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints]] and slaves belonging to [[White people|white]] converts. Later, most African American immigrants to Utah would migrate out for labor-related motivations. African Americans have traditionally been composed only a small part of the total population in Utah, with the [[2010 United States Census|2010 census]] placing the percentage of African Americans at 1.06%. Utah ranks 40th in the United States for [[List of U.S. states and territories by African-American population|total African American population]] and 43rd in percentage of residents who are African American.\n\n== Fur trapping and exploration period (early 1800s to 1847) ==\n[[File:Beckwourth citizen.jpg|thumb|James P. Beckwourth, fur trapper]]\nThe only record of African American presence in Utah prior to the arrival of [[Mormon pioneers|pioneers]] from The Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints was in the case of a few fur-trappers that traveled to the [[Utah Territory|Utah territory]]. [[James Beckwourth|James P. Beckwourth]] was a member of [[William Henry Ashley|William Ashley]]\u2019s [[Rocky Mountain Fur Company]], and spent several years off and on in Utah, especially in [[Cache Valley]] in the mid-1820\u2019s.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Jim Beckwourth: Black Mountain Man and War Chief of the Crows|last=Wilson|first=Elinor|publisher=University of Oklahoma Press|year=1972|isbn=978-0-8061-1012-7|location=Norman, Oklahoma, USA|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/jimbeckwourthbla0000wils}}</ref><ref name=\":2\">{{Cite book|title=A History of Blacks in Utah, 1825-1910|last=Coleman|first=Ronald Gerald|publisher=The University of Utah|year=1980|isbn=|location=Salt Lake City, Utah, USA|pages=26\u201330}}</ref>\n\n[[Jedediah Smith]] led several expeditions in the late 1820\u2019s to the Utah territory that involved African Americans Petre Ranne and Polette Labross.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\nIn 1843, on [[John C. Fr\u00e9mont|John C. Fremont]]\u2019s second westward expedition (which included the Utah territory), a young free African American named Jacob Dodson accompanied him.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\n== Utah slavery and arrival of Latter-day Saint pioneers (1847-1862) ==\n{{See also|History of slavery in Utah|Mormon pioneers}}\nOn July 22, 1847, pioneers from [[The Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints]], led by [[Brigham Young]], entered the Salt Lake Valley, fleeing [[Missouri]] and [[Illinois]] due to intense persecution. By the end of 1847, there were 12 African Americans living in the Salt Lake Valley, among them 8 slaves (including Oscar Crosby and Hark Lay), and a family of four free African Americans (Isaac and [[Jane Manning James]] family). [[Green Flake]], who had also arrived with the initial pioneer company, had gone with a group of pioneers to help others traveling across the plains.<ref name=\":2\" />[[File:Jane Elizabeth Manning James.jpg|thumb|Jane Elizabeth Manning James, free African American and early Utah pioneer]]By 1848 there were approximately 50 African Americans living in the Utah Territory after another pioneer company had arrived. 24 were slaves who had traveled from [[Mississippi]] led by [[John Brown (Mormon pioneer)|John Brown]], and they were joined by 12 other African Americans, mostly slaves, when they passed through [[Winter Quarters (North Omaha, Nebraska)|Winter Quarters]] in [[Nebraska]].<ref name=\":2\" />\n\nIn the 1850 US census, there were 50 \"colored\" people living in the Utah Territory, constituting 0.4% of the total territorial population.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.socialexplorer.com/tables/Census1850/R11872748|title=United States Census, 1850|last=|first=|date=|website=www.socialexplorer.com|language=en|access-date=2018-11-11}}</ref>\n\nIn the [[Compromise of 1850]], Utah was established as a [[Slave states and free states|slavery territory]], officially legalizing slavery in the Utah territory.\n\nIn 1852, the Utah Legislature, with input from the [[President of the Church|prophet]] and territorial governor Brigham Young, established the [[Act in Relation to Service]], which established a legal precedent for slavery in the territory (both for African Americans and [[Native Americans in the United States|Native Americans]]).<ref name=\":2\" /> These laws both protected the rights and proper treatment of the slaves while also legitimizing slavery and the slaves' duty to their masters. For example, it required that slaves be protected from unwilling transfer and sexual exploitation and be given proper treatment and schooling. On the other hand, slaves were required to submit dutifully to their masters' wishes and to punishment when necessary.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://blackpast.org/primarywest/utah-slave-code-1852|title=The Utah Territory Slave Code (1852) {{!}} The Black Past: Remembered and Reclaimed|website=blackpast.org|language=en|access-date=2018-11-11}}</ref>\n\nUnder Utah territorial law (before the [[Reconstruction Amendments]] were passed), African Americans could not [[Voting|vote]], serve on [[Jury|juries]], be elected to the legislature, or serve in the militia.<ref>{{Cite book|title=A Union, Utah, History|last=Madsen|first=Steven K.|publisher=Sons of Utah Pioneers|year=1981|isbn=|location=Utah|pages=}}</ref>\n\nOn June 19, 1862, the US Congress abolished slavery in Utah and all other US territories.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.freedmen.umd.edu/freeterr.htm|title=Emancipation in the Federal Territories, June 19, 1862|last=|first=|date=|website=www.freedmen.umd.edu|access-date=2018-11-13}}</ref>\n\n== Post-slavery period (1862-1950) ==\n{{See also|Racial segregation in the United States}}\n\n=== Population and distribution ===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+'''Census Data for African American Population in Utah from 1860 to 1950'''<ref name=\":6\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.socialexplorer.com/a9676d974c/explore|title=US Demography 1790 to Present|website=Social Explorer|language=en|access-date=2018-11-16}}</ref><ref name=\":4\">{{Cite web|url=http://gardner.utah.edu/bebr/Documents/studies/Utah_Minorities.pdf|title=Utah Minorities: The Story Told by 150 Years of Census Data|last=Perlich|first=Pamela S|last2=Eccles|first2=Davis S.|date=October 2002|website=University of Utah|access-date=}}</ref>\n!Year\n!Total Population\n!African American Population\n!Percentage of Population\n|-\n|1860\n|40,273\n|59\n|0.15%\n|-\n|1870\n|86,786\n|118\n|0.14%\n|-\n|1880\n|143,963\n|232\n|0.16%\n|-\n|1890\n|207,905\n|588\n|0.28%\n|-\n|1900\n|276,749\n|672\n|0.25%\n|-\n|1910\n|373,351\n|1,144\n|0.31%\n|-\n|1920\n|449,396\n|1,446\n|0.32%\n|-\n|1930\n|507,847\n|1,108\n|0.22%\n|-\n|1940\n|550,310\n|1,235\n|0.22%\n|-\n|1950\n|676,909\n|2,729\n|0.40%\n|}\nAs shown in the table above, the historic population of African Americans in Utah has been proportionally low.<ref name=\":4\" /> During the late 1800's, the greatest population of African Americans was in [[Salt Lake City]], followed by [[Uintah County, Utah|Uintah County]] due to the military presence, and [[Weber County, Utah|Weber County]] due to the railroad center located in [[Ogden, Utah|Ogden]].<ref name=\":2\" /> Unlike other western African American populations in the time period where single African American men was the norm, African American Utahns in the late 19th and early 20th centuries were mostly organized into family units.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\nUntil about 1870, most of the African American immigration to Utah was composed of converts to The Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints. After 1870, the majority of African American immigrants were immigrating for non-religious reasons.<ref name=\":2\" /> Despite this growth, the proportion of African Americans in Utah remained consistently low. One major reason for this trend was the [[Black people and Mormonism|lack of full acceptance of African Americans in the Latter-day Saint church]] (which lasted until [[1978 Revelation on Priesthood|1978]]), which resulted in a low incentive for African American converts and minimal [[Missionary (LDS Church)|missionary effort]] focused on [[Africa]]n countries.\n\n=== Industry ===\nThe [[United States Armed Forces|United States Military]] and the arrival of the railroads in Utah were perhaps the two biggest pull factors and employers for African Americans in this time period. In 1900, the most common occupation for African Americans was soldier, and second was \"servants and waiters\", which included the large number who worked for railroad companies. Agriculture and mining were also common occupations at the time.<ref name=\":2\" />\n[[File:Trinity AME Church SLC.jpeg|thumb|Trinity A.M.E. church in Salt Lake City]]\n\n=== African American community ===\nAs the African American community grew with the insurgence of non-religious motivated pioneers in the late 1800's, and especially grouped in places like Salt Lake City and Ogden, African American media, organizations, and churches (not The Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints) began to emerge in greater numbers. Between 1890 and 1891, the [[Trinity A.M.E. Church|first African Methodist Episcopal church]] in Utah was established in Salt Lake and became a focal point for the local African American community.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://npgallery.nps.gov/NRHP/GetAsset/NRHP/76001831_text|title=National Register of Historic Places Registration Form: Trinity African Methodist Episcopal Church|last=Smith|first=John S. H.|last2=Roberts|first2=Allen D.|date=June 11, 1976|website=National Park Service|access-date=November 27, 2018}}</ref> In the 1890's and early 1900's an African American [[Baptists|Baptist]] church was established in Salt Lake.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\n=== African American military units ===\n{{See also|Military history of African Americans}}\nThere were two notable segregated African American military units in Utah in the late 1800's: the [[9th Cavalry Regiment (United States)|Ninth Cavalry Regiment]] and the [[24th Infantry Regiment (United States)|24th Infantry Regiment]], stationed in [[Fort Duchesne, Utah|Fort Duchesne]] (Uintah County) and Salt Lake City respectively.<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite book|title=The Story of the Negro Pioneer|last=Carter|first=Kate B.|publisher=Daughters of Utah Pioneers|year=1865|isbn=|location=|pages=}}</ref> They were sent initially to help in the [[American Indian Wars|Indian Wars]] and in other necessary capacities. These two units composed a sizable portion of the African American population of Utah in this time period, notably giving Uintah county the second largest population of African Americans for a period of time.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\nFort Duchesne was reportedly segregated, but soldier-to-soldier interactions were generally not separated by race.<ref name=\":5\" />\n\n=== Discrimination/segregation ===\nThe Utah Legislature passed an [[Anti-miscegenation laws in the United States|anti-miscegenation law]] in 1888 which prohibited marriage \"between a negro and a white person\".<ref>{{Cite book|title=Compiled Laws of Utah, Volume II|last=|first=|publisher=Herbert Pembroke|year=1888|isbn=|location=Salt Lake City|pages=}}</ref>\n\nSome of the segregation present in Utah emerged in the late 1890's as a direct result of the arrival of the 24th Infantry to Salt Lake. Shop owners were reportedly concerned about African American soldiers entering their shops and restaurants, and were prompted to put up signs expressing their racial preferences.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\nUtah Schools were not formally segregated.<ref name=\":2\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://historytogo.utah.gov/utah_chapters/utah_today/thecivilrightsmovementinutah.html|title=The Civil Rights Movement in Utah|website=historytogo.utah.gov|access-date=2018-11-27}}</ref>\n\n== Desegregation and the civil rights movement (1950-1978) ==\n{{See also|Civil rights movement}}\n[[File:Salt lake city hotel utah 1925.jpg|thumb|Hotel Utah, Salt Lake City, circa 1925]]\nThe early 1950s brought much-anticipated change to the Utah community of African Americans. Previously, many famous African Americans, including the opera singer Maria Anderson and other prominent musicians such as [[Paul Robeson]], [[Harry Belafonte]], [[Ella Fitzgerald]], and [[Lionel Hampton]], all faced discrimination as they visited Utah. The [[Joseph Smith Memorial Building|Hotel Utah]] required them to abstain from eating at the hotel restaurant and to use the freight elevator.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.utahhumanities.org/stories/items/show/228|title=The Great White Palace: African American Segregation in Utah|last=Andersen|first=Rebecca|date=2012|website=|access-date=7 November 2018}}</ref> Others were unable to find accommodation in the hotels.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=https://heritage.utah.gov/history/uhg-civil-rights-movement-utah|title=The Civil Rights Movement in Utah - Utah Department of Heritage and Arts|date=2016-04-26|work=Utah Department of Heritage and Arts|access-date=2018-11-07|language=en-US}}</ref> Multiple governmental authorities, including the [[Ambassador to the United Nations|American Ambassador to the United Nations]], [[Ralph Bunche]], and Congressman [[Adam Clayton Powell Jr.|Adam Clayton Powell]], were also rejected by the hotel, forcing them to seek lodging in private homes.<ref name=\":1\" /> Bars, night clubs, and many dining establishments in Salt Lake City refused service to African Americans.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite journal|last=Peterson|first=F. Ross|date=Winter 2005|title=\"Blindside\": Utah on the Eve of Brown v. Board of Education|url=http://utahhistory.sdlhost.com/#/item/000000033000075/view|journal=Utah Historical Quarterly|volume=73|pages=4\u201320|via=}}</ref> The practice of segregation quickly began to dissolve, with public attractions such as [[Lagoon (amusement park)|Lagoon]], an amusement park in [[Farmington, Utah|Farmington]], allowing African Americans entry and use of the swimming pool and other park facilities.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\":0\" />\n\nOn the brink of ''[[Brown v. Board of Education]],'' Utah schools and universities tended to avoid hiring African American teachers, tending to favor whites for such positions.<ref name=\":1\" /> According to the [[NAACP]], no African American had taught in the Utah education system until late 1954, when the first black public school teacher was hired.<ref name=\":1\" /> Continued segregation existed not only in educational positions, but also in college sports until 1953, when the first black football players were accepted onto the [[Utah State University|Utah State Agricultural College]] football team.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nBy 1960, the African American population in Utah had grown by more than 50%, with census data showing an overall African American population of 4,148 people, comprising 0.47% of Utah's total population.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.socialexplorer.com|title=United States Census, 1960|last=|first=|date=|website=Social Explorer|access-date=6 November 2018}}</ref> In 1963, Utah's 75-year ban on miscegenation was lifted, allowing interracial marriage. Utah was the second-to-last state to repeal its anti-miscegenation statute, with [[Wyoming]] repealing in 1965.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Mason|first=Patrick Q|date=Spring 2008|title=The Prohibition of Interracial Marriage in Utah, 1888-1963|url=http://utahhistory.sdlhost.com/#/item/000000033000161/view|journal=Utah Historical Quarterly|volume=76|pages=108\u2013131|via=}}</ref>\n[[File:Spencer W. Kimball3.JPG|thumb|220x220px|Spencer W. Kimball]]\nA 1967 ''[[Daily Utah Chronicle]]'' interview with several African Americans in northern Utah provided insight into African-American views of racism and Utah's integration of civil rights policies. The interview reveals the African Americans, particularly youth, felt continued discouragement of interracial marriage, even after legalization, was wrong and unnecessary. Youth at [[West High School (Utah)|West High School]] reported that they felt welcome and received fair treatment at school. Students at [[Ogden High School]], however, complained about unfairness and prejudice from some teachers and principals. One woman felt offended at a realtor for not allowing her to look at house listings in predominantly white, middle-class East Salt Lake, taking her instead to the poor, dilapidated houses in West Salt Lake.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com|title=Negro Residents Enjoy Beehive State|last=Scott|first=Ron|date=25 Oct 1967|work=The Broad Axe|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nBy 1970, the African-American population in Utah had grown to 6,324.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.socialexplorer.com|title=United States Census, 1970|last=|first=|date=|website=Social Explorer|access-date=6 November 2018}}</ref> The Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints continued withholding priesthood authority from African Americans, causing tension and criticism within the church. [[David O. McKay]], President of the Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints, issued a letter to people struggling with confusion over the doctrine surrounding African Americans, stating resolutely that the time would come when African Americans would be given full rights in the church.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Mormonism and the Negro: an Explanation and Defense of the Doctrine of the Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-Day Saints in Regard to Negroes and Others of Negroid Blood|last=Stewart|first=John J.|publisher=Horizon|year=1978|isbn=|location=|pages=}}</ref>\n\nIn June 1978, [[Spencer W. Kimball]], then-president of The Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints issued [[1978 Revelation on Priesthood|Official Declaration 2]], which affirmed the Church's belief in the equality of all men and ended the long-standing practice of withholding certain church privileges from African American members, such as holding the priesthood and entering [[Temple (LDS Church)|temples]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.churchofjesuschrist.org/study/scriptures/dc-testament/od/2?lang=eng|title=Official Declaration 2|last=|first=|date=September 1978|website=The Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-Day Saints|access-date=7 November 2018}}</ref>\n\n== Modern day African-Americans (1978-today) ==\n=== Population ===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+Census Data for African American Population in Utah, 1980-2010<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.socialexplorer.com|title=United States Census, 1980|last=|first=|date=|website=Social Explorer|access-date=6 November 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.socialexplorer.com|title=United States Census, 1990|last=|first=|date=|website=Social Explorer|access-date=6 November 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.socialexplorer.com|title=United States Census, 2000|last=|first=|date=|website=Social Explorer|access-date=6 November 2018}}</ref><ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.socialexplorer.com|title=United States Census, 2010|last=|first=|date=|website=Social Explorer|access-date=6 November 2018}}</ref>\n!Year\n!Total Population\n!African American Population\n!Percentage of Population\n|-\n|1980\n|1,461,037\n|9,225\n|0.63%\n|-\n|1990\n|1,722,850\n|11,576\n|0.67%\n|-\n|2000\n|2,233,169\n|17,657\n|0.79%\n|-\n|2010\n|2,763,885\n|29,287\n|1.06%\n|}\nAfrican American population in Utah continued increasing at an accelerating rate, reaching just over 1% of the overall population during the 2010 census.<ref name=\":3\" />\n[[File:Lipofsky-Karl-Malone-32727.jpg|thumb|Karl Malone]]\n\n=== Sports ===\nUtah's college and professional sports scene includes hundreds of African American athletes, many of which receive great support from fans around the state. The roster for the [[Utah Jazz]], an [[National Basketball Association|NBA]] franchise based in Salt Lake City, has recruited well-known African American players such as [[Karl Malone]], [[Paul Millsap]], [[Donovan Mitchell]], [[Al Jefferson]], and [[Derrick Favors]], among many [[Utah Jazz all-time roster|others]].\n\nRacism still serves as a form of denigration during sports rivalries in Utah. An interview with an African American basketball player at the University of Utah revealed that [[racial slurs]] are still commonly shouted out during and after sports matches. Attempts of [[Violence|physical violence]] after games were also reported by the student.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://dailyutahchronicle.com/2018/02/12/black-athletes-struggles-outrun-racism/|title=Black Athletes' Struggles to Outrun Racism|last=Meservy|first=Brittni|date=February 12, 2018|work=Daily Utah Chronicle|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n=== Religion ===\nA 2009 Pew Forum study showed that approximately 3% of members of the Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints, the predominant religion in Utah, were African American.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.pewforum.org/2009/07/24/a-portrait-of-mormons-in-the-us/|title=A Portrait of Mormons in the U.S.|last=Pew Forum|date=2009-07-24|website=Pew Forum|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nThe Calvary Baptist Church, a well-known African American house of worship, has had a presence in Salt Lake City since 1898. Founded by a small group of African American women who gathered regularly to pray, the small group quickly expanded and moved from personal homes into a larger building. Reverend A. E. Reynolds was invited to act as the Calvary Baptist Church's first pastor and served for approximately three years. Membership continued to grow rapidly. Under the direction of Reverend France Davis, a new facility was constructed in 2001 for worship services. Each Sunday, around 300 African Americans gather at the Calvary Baptist Church to receive a free breakfast and hear Reverend Davis preach a sermon.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://calvaryslc.com/our-history/|title=Our History - Calvary Baptist Church|last=Calvary Baptist Church|date=2017-04-11|website=Calvary Baptist Church|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n=== Modern racial issues ===\nA 2013 study shows a large racial divide between East Salt Lake City and West Salt Lake City. The east is more affluent and is home to few African Americans and other minorities. The west, home to a much greater proportion of African Americans and other minorities, is a much more dilapidated, poverty-stricken area, with a 17.1% poverty rate according to the federally defined poverty line.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://ucdp.utah.edu/reports/HUD_Portal/FHEA/Salt_Lake_County/RCAPMarch2013.pdf|title=Racially Concentrated Areas of Poverty (RCAP) and Ethnically Concentrated Areas of Poverty (ECAP)|last=|first=|date=2013|website=Salt Lake Tribune|access-date=7 November 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe Salt Lake City chapter of the [[National Association for the Advancement of Colored People|National Association for the Advancement of Colored People (NAACP)]] claimed in 2017 to receive over 10 reports of racism weekly. Complaints include workplace unfairness, use of racial slurs, and threats of violence. Reports of racism are steadily increasing in the state.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thespectrum.com/story/news/2018/01/30/racism-workplace-social-media-inside-schools-utah/905356001/|title=Racism in Utah: In the workplace, on social media, and inside schools'|last=Havens|first=Emily|date=January 30, 2018|website=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n== Notable residents ==\n[[File:Al Jackson (42359850450).jpg|thumb|Alvin B. Jackson, Former Utah State Senator]]\n\n*[[James Beckwourth]]- fur trader and explorer\n*[[Green Flake]]- pioneer\n*[[Jane Manning James]]- pioneer\n*[[Elijah Abel]]- carpenter and church leader\n*[[Joseph Freeman (Mormon)|Joseph Freeman]]- first African American to receive the [[Priesthood (Latter Day Saints)|priesthood]] after the 1978 announcement by Spencer W. Kimball\n*[[Black Mormons#Wynetta Willis Martin|Wynetta Willis Martin]]- singer and [[Brigham Young University|BYU]] faculty member\n*[[Thurl Bailey]]- NBA basketball player\n*[[Byron Scott]]- NBA basketball coach and player\n*[[Alex Boy\u00e9]]- singer and actor\n*[[Alvin B. Jackson]]- state senator\n*[[Frank Jackson (basketball)|Frank Jackson]]- basketball player\n*[[Bryan Kehl]]- [[National Football League|NFL]] football player\n*[[Karl Malone]]- NBA basketball player\n*[[Mia Love]]- US congresswoman\n\n== See also ==\n{{Portal|United States|Utah}}\n*[[Black people and Mormonism]]\n*[[Black Mormons]]\n*[[History of Utah]]\n*[[National and ethnic cultures of Utah]]\n\n== References ==\n<references />\n\n{{African American topics}}\n\n[[Category:Ethnic groups in Utah]]\n[[Category:African-American cultural history]]\n[[Category:History of Utah]]\n[[Category:African diaspora history]]\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: 1890's and early 1900's \u2192 1890s and early 1900s, 1800's \u2192 1800s (4)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/History_of_African_Americans_in_Utah"}
{"title_page": "Parry Sound, Ontario", "text_new": "{{about|the town|the body of water in Georgian Bay, Ontario|Parry Sound}}\n<!-- Infobox begins -->\n{{Infobox settlement\n| name                            = Parry Sound\n| official_name                   = Town of Parry Sound\n| settlement_type                 = [[List of towns in Ontario|Town]] ([[List of municipalities in Ontario#Single-tier municipalities|single-tier]])\n| other_name                      = \n| native_name                     = <!-- for cities whose native name is not in English -->\n| nickname                        = \n| motto                           = \n| image_skyline                   = Aerial view of Parry Sound.jpg\n| imagesize                       = \n| image_caption                   = Looking over the town and the sound\n| image_flag                      = \n| flag_size                       = \n| image_seal                      = \n| seal_size                       = \n| image_shield                    = \n| shield_size                     = \n| image_blank_emblem              = \n| blank_emblem_size               = \n| image_map                       = \n| mapsize                         = \n| map_caption                     = \n| pushpin_map                     = Canada Southern Ontario#Canada\n| pushpin_mapsize                 = 200\n| subdivision_type                = Country\n| subdivision_name                = Canada\n| subdivision_type1               = [[Provinces and territories of Canada|Province]]\n| subdivision_name1               = Ontario\n| subdivision_type2               = District\n| subdivision_name2               = [[Parry Sound District|Parry Sound]]\n| subdivision_type3               = \n| subdivision_name3               = \n| subdivision_type4               = \n| subdivision_name4               = \n| government_type                 = \n| leader_title                    = Mayor\n| leader_name                     = Jamie McGarvey\n| leader_title1                   = Governing Body\n| leader_name1                    = Parry Sound Town Council\n| leader_title2                   = MP\n| leader_name2                    = [[Scott Aitchison]] ([[Conservative Party of Canada|CPC]])\n| leader_title3                   = MPPs\n| leader_name3                    = [[Norm Miller]] ([[Progressive Conservative Party of Ontario|PC]])\n| leader_title4                   = \n| leader_name4                    = \n| established_title               = Established <!-- Settled -->\n| established_date                = 1857\n| established_title2              = <!-- Incorporated (town) -->\n| established_date2               = \n| established_title3              = <!-- Incorporated (city) -->\n| established_date3               = \n| area_magnitude                  = \n| unit_pref                       = <!--Enter: Imperial, if Imperial (metric) is desired-->\n| area_footnotes                  = <ref name=SC16/>\n| area_total_km2                  = \n| area_land_km2                   = 13.40\n| area_water_km2                  = \n| area_water_percent              = \n| population_as_of                = 2016\n| population_footnotes            = <ref name=SC16>{{cite web|url=http://www12.statcan.gc.ca/census-recensement/2016/dp-pd/prof/details/page.cfm?Lang=E&Geo1=CSD&Code1=3549032&Geo2=CD&Code2=3549&Data=Count&SearchText=parry%20sound&SearchType=Begins&SearchPR=01&B1=All&TABID=1 |title=2016 Census Profile: Parry Sound, Town |publisher=[[Statistics Canada]]|accessdate=March 8, 2019}}</ref>\n| population_demonym              = Parry Soundian, Parry Sounder\n| population_note                 = \n| population_total                = 6408\n| population_density_km2          = 478.2\n| timezone                        = [[Eastern Time Zone|EST]]\n| utc_offset                      = \u221205:00\n| timezone_DST                    = EDT\n| utc_offset_DST                  = \u221204:00\n| coordinates                     = {{coord|45|20|N|80|02|W|region:CA-ON|display=inline,title}}\n| elevation_footnotes             = <!--for references: use <ref> tags-->\n| elevation_m                     = \n| postal_code_type                = [[Canadian postal code#Forward sortation areas|Forward sortation area]]\n| postal_code                     = [[List of P postal codes of Canada|P2A]]\n| area_code                       = [[Area code 705|705]] & [[Area code 249|249]]\n| blank_name                      = [[List of highways in Ontario|Highways]]\n| blank_info                      = {{jcon|Hwy|400}}<br>{{jct|state=ON|Hwy|69|TCH}}<br>{{jcon|Hwy|124}}<br>{{jcon|Hwy|518}}\n| website                         = [www.parrysound.ca]\n| footnotes                       = \n}}\n <!-- Infobox ends -->\n\n'''Parry Sound''' is a town in [[Ontario]], Canada, located on the eastern shore of the [[Parry Sound|sound after which it is named]].  Parry Sound is located {{convert|160|km|abbr=on}} south of [[Greater Sudbury|Sudbury]] and {{convert|225|km|mi|abbr=on}} north of [[Toronto]]. It is a single tier government located in the territorial District of Parry Sound which has no second tier County, Regional or District level of government. Parry Sound is a popular [[cottage|cottage country]] region for [[Southern Ontario]] residents. It also has the world's deepest natural freshwater port.<ref name=\"Society2007\">{{cite book|title=Canadian Geographic|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=knUZAQAAMAAJ|accessdate=11 April 2012|volume=127|year=2007|publisher=Royal Canadian Geographical Society|page=82|quote= Parry Sound, the world's deepest freshwater port, lends some measure to what I mean by Ontario Lake Country}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n\nDuring the early part of the 20th century, the area was a popular subject for the many scenic art works of [[Tom Thomson]] and members of the [[Group of Seven (artists)|Group of Seven]]. There was a slight decline in economic activity shortly after World War I with [[J.R. Booth]]'s construction of a rival town, [[Depot Harbour, Ontario|Depot Harbour]] on nearby [[Parry Island, Ontario|Parry Island]], but this setback was overcome through later developments in tourism and commerce, and the accidental destruction by fire of the entire town of Depot Harbour on August 14, 1945.\n\nThe body of water that gives the town its name was surveyed and named by Captain [[Henry Bayfield]] in the 19th century, in honour of the Arctic explorer Sir [[William Edward Parry]]. In 1857, the modern townsite was established near the [[Ojibwa]] village of [[Wasauksing First Nation|Wasauksing]] (\"shining shore\") at the mouth of the [[Seguin River]]. Parry Sound was incorporated as a town in 1887.  In the late 19th century, [[railway|rail]] service was established, making the town an important depot along the rail lines to [[Western Canada]].\n\nIn 1916, a [[cordite]] factory was established in the nearby town of [[Nobel, Ontario|Nobel]] for the [[Imperial Munitions Board]]. In the late 1920s and early 1930s, an [[explosives]] and [[munitions]] factory was also built at Nobel, making Parry Sound an important part of both the First World War and the Second World War effort.\n\n== Culture ==\n[[File:downtownParrySound.jpg|thumb|left|View of downtown Parry Sound near the intersection of Seguin and James Streets. A portion of the Sound and the CP railway trestle can be seen in the distance.]]\nParry Sound is the birthplace of hockey legend [[Bobby Orr]], the namesake of the local community centre and the town's own [[Bobby Orr Hall of Fame]]. In Orr's best-selling autobiography, ''[[Orr: My Story (book)|Orr: My Story]]'', he speaks highly of Parry Sound, the friends and family who resided there and the happy childhood he had living in that part of Canada.<ref name=\"Orr\">Orr, Bobby (2013) ''Bobby Orr: My Story''. New York: G.P. Putnam. Retrieved March 31, 2014 [http://www.penguin.ca/nf/Book/BookDisplay/0,,9780670066971,00.html]</ref><ref>Cowles, Gregory (October 25, 2013) \"Inside the List\" ''The New York Times''. Retrieved March 27, 2014 [https://www.nytimes.com/2013/11/03/books/review/inside-the-list.html?action=click&module=Search&region=searchResults%230&version=&url=http%3A%2F%2Fquery.nytimes.com%2Fsearch%2Fsitesearch%2F%3Faction%3Dclick%26region%3DMasthead%26pgtype%3DHomepage%26module%3DSearchSubmit%26contentCollection%3DHomepage%26t%3Dqry53%23%2F%2522Bobby%2BOrr%2522%2F365days%2F&_r=0]</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Best Sellers|url=https://www.nytimes.com/best-sellers-books/2013-11-03/combined-print-and-e-book-nonfiction/list.html|newspaper=The New York Times|accessdate=5 April 2014}}</ref>\n\nCanadian actor [[Don Harron]]'s stage character Charlie Farquharson remains one of the town's most cherished personalities. Former Ontario premier [[Ernie Eves]] also called the town home for many years; he was the [[Member of Provincial Parliament (Ontario)|MPP]] for the [[Parry Sound\u2014Muskoka (provincial electoral district)|Parry Sound\u2014Muskoka]] riding from 1981 through 2001.\n\nThe town is home to several cultural festivals, including the [[Festival of the Sound]] classical music festival, an annual [[dragonboat]] race and a [[buskers]]' festival which takes place as part of the town's [[Canada Day]] festivities. The [[Charles W. Stockey Centre for the Performing Arts]] serves as the principal performance venue during the Festival of the Sound, and also hosts concerts, live theatre and other cultural events throughout the year.\n\n==Recreation and sports==\nThere are several [[provincial park]]s in the Parry Sound area, including [[Oastler Lake Provincial Park|Oastler Lake]], [[The Massasauga Provincial Park|The Massasauga]] and [[Killbear Provincial Park|Killbear]], as well as numerous provincial [[Nature Reserve Park (Ontario)|conservation reserve]]s, including the Georgian Bay Biosphere Reserve, one of only 13 UNESCO sites in Canada. The eastern coast of Georgian Bay where Parry Sound is located is known as the \"30,000 Islands\" and is considered the world's largest freshwater archipelago.  It covers 347,000 hectares of shoreline ecosystem, and over 100 species of animals and plants that are at risk in Canada and Ontario, including unique reptiles and amphibians.  Parry Sound's Aspen Valley Wildlife Sanctuary<ref>[http://www.aspenvalleywildlifesanctuary.com Aspen Valley Wildlife Sanctuary]</ref> cares for injured and orphaned animals, and offers an informational and interpretive centre for wildlife education.  A 230-kilometre recreational trail, the Park-to-Park Trail, connects Killbear with [[Algonquin Provincial Park]] in two locations, to the south at [[Dwight, Ontario|Dwight]], and farther north, east of [[Kearney, Ontario|Kearney]].<ref>[http://www.parktoparktrail.com/ The Park-to-Park Trail]</ref>\n\n[[File:ON ParrySound tango7174.jpg|thumb|230px|Departure point at the harbour, for the sightseeing tours of the 30,000 Islands]]\n\nParry Sound, and much of Northern Ontario, are well known for their tourism businesses.  Accommodation businesses range from hotels and full service resorts to lodges and camping grounds.  Sightseeing tours of the 30,000 Islands are offered by Georgian Bay Airways,<ref>[http://www.georgianbayairways.com Georgian Bay Airways]</ref> and the Island Queen and MV Chippawa<ref>[http://www.spiritofthesound.ca M.V. Chippewa]</ref> cruise ships. [[kayak]] and [[canoe]] rentals and tours are available during the summer, as well as winter sporting gear rentals during the winter.  The town is home to an annual ATV Jamboree<ref>[http://www.springjam.ca Spring Jam]</ref> and guided ATV tours of the region's wilderness are available throughout the year.<ref>[http://bearclawtours.com Bear Claw Tours]</ref>  There are several [[golf courses]] located in and near Parry Sound; [[ice hockey]], [[fishing]] and [[softball]] are also popular recreational sports in the area.  Famous NHLer [[Bobby Orr]] played minor hockey for the Parry Sound Shamrocks. Aidan Dudas also played for the Shamrocks, and currently plays for the [[Owen Sound Attack]] of the [[Ontario Hockey League|OHL]], and was selected in the fourth round (113th overall) of the [[2019 NHL Draft]] by the [[Los Angeles Kings]]. The town had a junior team also called the Shamrocks for a short period of time who reached the [[Northern Ontario Junior Hockey Association]] championship finals in 1998 and 1999 before the team folded in 2003.\n\n==Transportation==\n[[Image:Parry Sound ON.jpg|thumb|right|230px|Harbour of Parry Sound]]\nParry Sound is located along a highway which currently bears the dual designation of [[Ontario Highway 69|Highway 69]]/[[Ontario Highway 400|Highway 400]]. From the opening of this [[freeway]] alignment in 2004 until October 26, 2010, a point one kilometre north of Parry Sound's Bowes Street/McDougall Road interchange was the terminus of Highway 400, but the freeway now begins 17 kilometres further north, at [[Ontario Highway 559|Highway 559]] north of [[Nobel, Ontario|Nobel]].<ref name=\"nobel\">{{cite news\n |title       = $177-million section of highway now open\n |first       = Cameron\n |last        = Ginn\n |publisher   = Metroland Media Group\n |work        = Cottage Country Now\n |date        = October 27, 2010\n |url         = http://www.cottagecountrynow.ca/community/parrysound/article/893665\n |accessdate  = October 28, 2010\n |url-status     = dead\n |archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20110424214321/http://www.cottagecountrynow.ca/community/parrysound/article/893665\n |archivedate = April 24, 2011\n}}</ref> The former alignment of Highway 69 from Parry Sound southerly to [[Holmur, Ontario|Holmur]] now has the street name [[Oastler Park Drive]] and serves as the main access road to [[Oastler Lake Provincial Park]].\n\nThe western termini of [[Ontario Highway 124|Highway 124]], which extends easterly to [[Sundridge, Ontario|Sundridge]], and [[Ontario Highway 518|Highway 518]], which heads east to [[Kearney, Ontario|Kearney]], are both located just outside Parry Sound's town limits.\n\nBus service from [[Toronto]] is available by [[Ontario Northland Motor Coach Services]], the government-owned transportation company, and buses arrive daily en route to Sudbury.  In addition, [[Via Rail]]'s ''[[Canadian (train)|Canadian]]'' (Toronto \u2013 [[Vancouver]]) [[Transcontinental railroad|transcontinental]] passenger train serve [[Parry Sound railway station]]s three times a week both east- and westbound. Westbound passenger as well as [[Canadian Pacific Railway]] and [[Canadian National Railway]] freight trains are carried over the Seguin River by the [[Parry Sound CPR Trestle]], a visible presence in the centre of town.\n\nThe town is served by the [[Parry Sound Area Municipal Airport]] and the [[List of heliports in Canada#188|Parry Sound Medical Heliport]], as well as numerous small water [[aerodromes]]:\n* [[Parry Sound Harbour Water Aerodrome]] (CPS1)\n* [[Parry Sound/Deep Bay Water Aerodrome]] (CPT6)\n* [[Parry Sound/Derbyshire Island Water Aerodrome]] (CDS6)\n* [[Parry Sound/Frying Pan Island-Sans Souci Water Aerodrome]] (CPS9)\n* [[Parry Sound/Huron Island Water Aerodrome]] (CPS8)\n* [[Parry Sound/St. Waleran Island Water Aerodrome]] (CPD6)\n\nThe Big Sound Marina<ref>[http://www.bigsoundmarina.com Big Sound Marina]</ref> is a 120-serviced slip marina on Georgian Bay for transient vessels up to {{convert|60|ft|m|0}}.\n\n==Climate==\n\nParry Sound has a humid continental climate, with some quite-unusual local variations in cloudiness and precipitation for this climate, resulting from its location on the eastern shore of the large body of water comprising Parry Sound and Lake Huron to its west. Parry Sound's annual temperature regime reflects a cool-summer [[humid continental climate]] ([[K\u00f6ppen climate classification|Koppen]] Dfb), with January average temperatures of {{convert|-9.0|C}} and July average temperatures near {{convert|20.2|C}}, and the usual minimal seasonal lag typical of continental climates, i.e. January as the coldest month, July as the warmest.\n\nMuch more unusual (for Dfb climates) is Parry Sound's average annual cycle of precipitation, and cloudiness vs. sunshine. With its location on the eastern side of large bodies of water, where prevailing winds and weather come from the west (typical in the mid-latitude Northern Hemisphere), Parry Sound experiences an exceptionally strong [[Lake-effect snow|lake effect]]. From spring to mid-summer, this means lake waters are cooler than nearby land areas, resulting in diminished intensity of low pressure systems and less precipitation, but alternation of low clouds and fog (resulting from warmer air passing over snow-covered ground, frequent into May most years) with occasional sunshine, especially once the long winter's snow cover has melted (mostly May through July). Parry Sound's average driest month is July; here, thunderstorms are rare, due to cool lake waters inhibiting the combination of heat and humidity that fuels thunderstorm activity over areas like the central, southern and eastern United States.\n\nFrom September to January in Parry Sound the lake effect reverses its stabilizing effect from spring into mid-summer, becoming destabilizing. During these months, nearby waters release their stored warmth from the summer season, and increasingly strong polar and Arctic air outbreaks pass over these still-relatively-warm waters before hitting Parry Sound. This results in heavy [[cumulus cloud]] formation, instability rain showers (in September and October), transitioning toward heavy snow showers and squalls as temperatures continue to drop from November to January. Parry Sound's average monthly precipitation exceeds {{convert|100|mm|abbr=on}} inches every month from September to January - but this pattern peaks in December, the year's average wettest month, which averages over {{convert|137|mm|abbr=on}} of precipitation, mostly carried by that month's average of {{convert|101.6|cm|abbr=on}} of snow, followed by January's snowfall average of {{convert|91.2|cm|abbr=on}}. Such heavy winter-month precipitation and snowfall figures are virtually nonexistent in humid continental climates, which tend to exist away from large bodies of water. As winter transitions toward spring, snowfall drops sharply by March, when lake and land temperatures nearly equalize. In winter, the heavy lake-effect snowfall is augmented by snowfall from sometimes-strong low-pressure systems (mid-latitude [[cyclone]]s) that often converge on the [[Great Lakes]] and areas further east.\n\nOverall, Parry Sound experiences a typical humid continental, cool-summer climate type in terms of temperatures - but a highly unusual climate regime in precipitation and cloudiness; the year's driest months are generally from March through July, while its wettest months are from September to January, with autumnal lake effect producing cloudy skies and heavy rainfall from September into November, followed by extremely heavy snowfall in December and January.\n\nThe highest temperature ever recorded in Parry Sound was {{convert|37.8|C}} on July 6, 1921. The coldest temperature ever recorded was {{convert|-41.1|C|0}} on February 12. 1967.<ref name=\"July 1921\"/><ref name=\"February 1967\"/>\n\n{{Weather box\n|location = Parry Sound, 1981\u22122010 normals, extremes 1875\u2212present\n|metric first = Y\n|single line = Y\n|Jan record high C = 13.9\n|Feb record high C = 14.4\n|Mar record high C = 27.0\n|Apr record high C = 31.0\n|May record high C = 32.5\n|Jun record high C = 36.1\n|Jul record high C = 37.8\n|Aug record high C = 37.2\n|Sep record high C = 35.0\n|Oct record high C = 28.9\n|Nov record high C = 21.7\n|Dec record high C = 15.5\n|year record high C = 37.8\n|Jan high C = \u22124.4\n|Feb high C = \u22122.2\n|Mar high C = 2.6\n|Apr high C = 10.5\n|May high C = 16.9\n|Jun high C = 21.1\n|Jul high C = 25.1\n|Aug high C = 23.8\n|Sep high C = 19.0\n|Oct high C = 12.4\n|Nov high C = 5.1\n|Dec high C = -1.4\n|year high C = 10.7\n|Jan mean C