n| population_as_of                = 2016\n| population_footnotes            = <ref name=SC16>{{cite web|url=http://www12.statcan.gc.ca/census-recensement/2016/dp-pd/prof/details/page.cfm?Lang=E&Geo1=CSD&Code1=3549032&Geo2=CD&Code2=3549&Data=Count&SearchText=parry%20sound&SearchType=Begins&SearchPR=01&B1=All&TABID=1 |title=2016 Census Profile: Parry Sound, Town |publisher=[[Statistics Canada]]|accessdate=March 8, 2019}}</ref>\n| population_demonym              = Parry Soundian, Parry Sounder\n| population_note                 = \n| population_total                = 6408\n| population_density_km2          = 478.2\n| timezone                        = [[Eastern Time Zone|EST]]\n| utc_offset                      = \u221205:00\n| timezone_DST                    = EDT\n| utc_offset_DST                  = \u221204:00\n| coordinates                     = {{coord|45|20|N|80|02|W|region:CA-ON|display=inline,title}}\n| elevation_footnotes             = <!--for references: use <ref> tags-->\n| elevation_m                     = \n| postal_code_type                = [[Canadian postal code#Forward sortation areas|Forward sortation area]]\n| postal_code                     = [[List of P postal codes of Canada|P2A]]\n| area_code                       = [[Area code 705|705]] & [[Area code 249|249]]\n| blank_name                      = [[List of highways in Ontario|Highways]]\n| blank_info                      = {{jcon|Hwy|400}}<br>{{jct|state=ON|Hwy|69|TCH}}<br>{{jcon|Hwy|124}}<br>{{jcon|Hwy|518}}\n| website                         = [www.parrysound.ca]\n| footnotes                       = \n}}\n <!-- Infobox ends -->\n\n'''Parry Sound''' is a town in [[Ontario]], Canada, located on the eastern shore of the [[Parry Sound|sound after which it is named]].  Parry Sound is located {{convert|160|km|abbr=on}} south of [[Greater Sudbury|Sudbury]] and {{convert|225|km|mi|abbr=on}} north of [[Toronto]]. It is a single tier government located in the territorial District of Parry Sound which has no second tier County, Regional or District level of government. Parry Sound is a popular [[cottage|cottage country]] region for [[Southern Ontario]] residents. It also has the world's deepest natural freshwater port.<ref name=\"Society2007\">{{cite book|title=Canadian Geographic|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=knUZAQAAMAAJ|accessdate=11 April 2012|volume=127|year=2007|publisher=Royal Canadian Geographical Society|page=82|quote= Parry Sound, the world's deepest freshwater port, lends some measure to what I mean by Ontario Lake Country}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n\nDuring the early part of the 20th century, the area was a popular subject for the many scenic art works of [[Tom Thomson]] and members of the [[Group of Seven (artists)|Group of Seven]]. There was a slight decline in economic activity shortly after World War I with [[J.R. Booth]]'s construction of a rival town, [[Depot Harbour, Ontario|Depot Harbour]] on nearby [[Parry Island, Ontario|Parry Island]], but this setback was overcome through later developments in tourism and commerce, and the accidental destruction by fire of the entire town of Depot Harbour on August 14, 1945.\n\nThe body of water that gives the town its name was surveyed and named by Captain [[Henry Bayfield]] in the 19th century, in honour of the Arctic explorer Sir [[William Edward Parry]]. In 1857, the modern townsite was established near the [[Ojibwa]] village of [[Wasauksing First Nation|Wasauksing]] (\"shining shore\") at the mouth of the [[Seguin River]]. Parry Sound was incorporated as a town in 1887.  In the late 19th century, [[railway|rail]] service was established, making the town an important depot along the rail lines to [[Western Canada]].\n\nIn 1916, a [[cordite]] factory was established in the nearby town of [[Nobel, Ontario|Nobel]] for the [[Imperial Munitions Board]]. In the late 1920s and early 1930s, an [[explosives]] and [[munitions]] factory was also built at Nobel, making Parry Sound an important part of both the First World War and the Second World War effort.\n\n== Culture ==\n[[File:downtownParrySound.jpg|thumb|left|View of downtown Parry Sound near the intersection of Seguin and James Streets. A portion of the Sound and the CP railway trestle can be seen in the distance.]]\nParry Sound is the birthplace of hockey legend [[Bobby Orr]], the namesake of the local community centre and the town's own [[Bobby Orr Hall of Fame]]. In Orr's best-selling autobiography, ''[[Orr: My Story (book)|Orr: My Story]]'', he speaks highly of Parry Sound, the friends and family who resided there and the happy childhood he had living in that part of Canada.<ref name=\"Orr\">Orr, Bobby (2013) ''Bobby Orr: My Story''. New York: G.P. Putnam. Retrieved March 31, 2014 [http://www.penguin.ca/nf/Book/BookDisplay/0,,9780670066971,00.html]</ref><ref>Cowles, Gregory (October 25, 2013) \"Inside the List\" ''The New York Times''. Retrieved March 27, 2014 [https://www.nytimes.com/2013/11/03/books/review/inside-the-list.html?action=click&module=Search&region=searchResults%230&version=&url=http%3A%2F%2Fquery.nytimes.com%2Fsearch%2Fsitesearch%2F%3Faction%3Dclick%26region%3DMasthead%26pgtype%3DHomepage%26module%3DSearchSubmit%26contentCollection%3DHomepage%26t%3Dqry53%23%2F%2522Bobby%2BOrr%2522%2F365days%2F&_r=0]</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Best Sellers|url=https://www.nytimes.com/best-sellers-books/2013-11-03/combined-print-and-e-book-nonfiction/list.html|newspaper=The New York Times|accessdate=5 April 2014}}</ref>\n\nCanadian actor [[Don Harron]]'s stage character Charlie Farquharson remains one of the town's most cherished personalities. Former Ontario premier [[Ernie Eves]] also called the town home for many years; he was the [[Member of Provincial Parliament (Ontario)|MPP]] for the [[Parry Sound\u2014Muskoka (provincial electoral district)|Parry Sound\u2014Muskoka]] riding from 1981 through 2001.\n\nThe town is home to several cultural festivals, including the [[Festival of the Sound]] classical music festival, an annual [[dragonboat]] race and a [[buskers]]' festival which takes place as part of the town's [[Canada Day]] festivities. The [[Charles W. Stockey Centre for the Performing Arts]] serves as the principal performance venue during the Festival of the Sound, and also hosts concerts, live theatre and other cultural events throughout the year.\n\n==Recreation and sports==\nThere are several [[provincial park]]s in the Parry Sound area, including [[Oastler Lake Provincial Park|Oastler Lake]], [[The Massasauga Provincial Park|The Massasauga]] and [[Killbear Provincial Park|Killbear]], as well as numerous provincial [[Nature Reserve Park (Ontario)|conservation reserve]]s, including the Georgian Bay Biosphere Reserve, one of only 13 UNESCO sites in Canada. The eastern coast of Georgian Bay where Parry Sound is located is known as the \"30,000 Islands\" and is considered the world's largest freshwater archipelago.  It covers 347,000 hectares of shoreline ecosystem, and over 100 species of animals and plants that are at risk in Canada and Ontario, including unique reptiles and amphibians.  Parry Sound's Aspen Valley Wildlife Sanctuary<ref>[http://www.aspenvalleywildlifesanctuary.com Aspen Valley Wildlife Sanctuary]</ref> cares for injured and orphaned animals, and offers an informational and interpretive centre for wildlife education.  A 230-kilometre recreational trail, the Park-to-Park Trail, connects Killbear with [[Algonquin Provincial Park]] in two locations, to the south at [[Dwight, Ontario|Dwight]], and farther north, east of [[Kearney, Ontario|Kearney]].<ref>[http://www.parktoparktrail.com/ The Park-to-Park Trail]</ref>\n\n[[File:ON ParrySound tango7174.jpg|thumb|230px|Departure point at the harbour, for the sightseeing tours of the 30,000 Islands]]\n\nParry Sound, and much of Northern Ontario, are well known for their tourism businesses.  Accommodation businesses range from hotels and full service resorts to lodges and camping grounds.  Sightseeing tours of the 30,000 Islands are offered by Georgian Bay Airways,<ref>[http://www.georgianbayairways.com Georgian Bay Airways]</ref> and the Island Queen and MV Chippawa<ref>[http://www.spiritofthesound.ca M.V. Chippewa]</ref> cruise ships. [[kayak]] and [[canoe]] rentals and tours are available during the summer, as well as winter sporting gear rentals during the winter.  The town is home to an annual ATV Jamboree<ref>[http://www.springjam.ca Spring Jam]</ref> and guided ATV tours of the region's wilderness are available throughout the year.<ref>[http://bearclawtours.com Bear Claw Tours]</ref>  There are several [[golf courses]] located in and near Parry Sound; [[ice hockey]], [[fishing]] and [[softball]] are also popular recreational sports in the area.  Famous NHLer [[Bobby Orr]] played minor hockey for the Parry Sound Shamrocks. Aidan Dudas also played for the Shamrocks, and currently plays for the [[Owen Sound Attack]] of the [[Ontario Hockey League|OHL]], and was selected in the fourth round (113th overall) of the [[2019 NHL Draft]] by the [[Los Angeles Kings]]. The town had a junior team also called the Shamrocks for a short period of time who reached the [[Northern Ontario Junior Hockey Association]] championship finals in 1998 and 1999 before the team folded in 2003.\n\n==Transportation==\n[[Image:Parry Sound ON.jpg|thumb|right|230px|Harbour of Parry Sound]]\nParry Sound is located along a highway which currently bears the dual designation of [[Ontario Highway 69|Highway 69]]/[[Ontario Highway 400|Highway 400]]. From the opening of this [[freeway]] alignment in 2004 until October 26, 2010, a point one kilometre north of Parry Sound's Bowes Street/McDougall Road interchange was the terminus of Highway 400, but the freeway now begins 17 kilometres further north, at [[Ontario Highway 559|Highway 559]] north of [[Nobel, Ontario|Nobel]].<ref name=\"nobel\">{{cite news\n |title       = $177-million section of highway now open\n |first       = Cameron\n |last        = Ginn\n |publisher   = Metroland Media Group\n |work        = Cottage Country Now\n |date        = October 27, 2010\n |url         = http://www.cottagecountrynow.ca/community/parrysound/article/893665\n |accessdate  = October 28, 2010\n |url-status     = dead\n |archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20110424214321/http://www.cottagecountrynow.ca/community/parrysound/article/893665\n |archivedate = April 24, 2011\n}}</ref> The former alignment of Highway 69 from Parry Sound southerly to [[Holmur, Ontario|Holmur]] now has the street name [[Oastler Park Drive]] and serves as the main access road to [[Oastler Lake Provincial Park]].\n\nThe western termini of [[Ontario Highway 124|Highway 124]], which extends easterly to [[Sundridge, Ontario|Sundridge]], and [[Ontario Highway 518|Highway 518]], which heads east to [[Kearney, Ontario|Kearney]], are both located just outside Parry Sound's town limits.\n\nBus service from [[Toronto]] is available by [[Ontario Northland Motor Coach Services]], the government-owned transportation company, and buses arrive daily en route to Sudbury.  In addition, [[Via Rail]]'s ''[[Canadian (train)|Canadian]]'' (Toronto \u2013 [[Vancouver]]) [[Transcontinental railroad|transcontinental]] passenger train serve [[Parry Sound railway station]]s three times a week both east- and westbound. Westbound passenger as well as [[Canadian Pacific Railway]] and [[Canadian National Railway]] freight trains are carried over the Seguin River by the [[Parry Sound CPR Trestle]], a visible presence in the centre of town.\n\nThe town is served by the [[Parry Sound Area Municipal Airport]] and the [[List of heliports in Canada#188|Parry Sound Medical Heliport]], as well as numerous small water [[aerodromes]]:\n* [[Parry Sound Harbour Water Aerodrome]] (CPS1)\n* [[Parry Sound/Deep Bay Water Aerodrome]] (CPT6)\n* [[Parry Sound/Derbyshire Island Water Aerodrome]] (CDS6)\n* [[Parry Sound/Frying Pan Island-Sans Souci Water Aerodrome]] (CPS9)\n* [[Parry Sound/Huron Island Water Aerodrome]] (CPS8)\n* [[Parry Sound/St. Waleran Island Water Aerodrome]] (CPD6)\n\nThe Big Sound Marina<ref>[http://www.bigsoundmarina.com Big Sound Marina]</ref> is a 120-serviced slip marina on Georgian Bay for transient vessels up to {{convert|60|ft|m|0}}.\n\n==Climate==\n\nParry Sound has a humid continental climate, with some quite-unusual local variations in cloudiness and precipitation for this climate, resulting from its location on the eastern shore of the large body of water comprising Parry Sound and Lake Huron to its west. Parry Sound's annual temperature regime reflects a cool-summer [[humid continental climate]] ([[K\u00f6ppen climate classification|Koppen]] Dfb), with January average temperatures of {{convert|-9.0|C}} and July average temperatures near {{convert|20.2|C}}, and the usual minimal seasonal lag typical of continental climates, i.e. January as the coldest month, July as the warmest.\n\nMuch more unusual (for Dfb climates) is Parry Sound's average annual cycle of precipitation, and cloudiness vs. sunshine. With its location on the eastern side of large bodies of water, where prevailing winds and weather come from the west (typical in the mid-latitude Northern Hemisphere), Parry Sound experiences an exceptionally strong [[Lake-effect snow|lake effect]]. From spring to mid-summer, this means lake waters are cooler than nearby land areas, resulting in diminished intensity of low pressure systems and less precipitation, but alternation of low clouds and fog (resulting from warmer air passing over snow-covered ground, frequent into May most years) with occasional sunshine, especially once the long winter's snow cover has melted (mostly May through July). Parry Sound's average driest month is July; here, thunderstorms are rare, due to cool lake waters inhibiting the combination of heat and humidity that fuels thunderstorm activity over areas like the central, southern and eastern United States.\n\nFrom September to January in Parry Sound the lake effect reverses its stabilizing effect from spring into mid-summer, becoming destabilizing. During these months, nearby waters release their stored warmth from the summer season, and increasingly strong polar and Arctic air outbreaks pass over these still-relatively-warm waters before hitting Parry Sound. This results in heavy [[cumulus cloud]] formation, instability rain showers (in September and October), transitioning toward heavy snow showers and squalls as temperatures continue to drop from November to January. Parry Sound's average monthly precipitation exceeds {{convert|100|mm|abbr=on}} inches every month from September to January - but this pattern peaks in December, the year's average wettest month, which averages over {{convert|137|mm|abbr=on}} of precipitation, mostly carried by that month's average of {{convert|101.6|cm|abbr=on}} of snow, followed by January's snowfall average of {{convert|91.2|cm|abbr=on}}. Such heavy winter-month precipitation and snowfall figures are virtually nonexistent in humid continental climates, which tend to exist away from large bodies of water. As winter transitions toward spring, snowfall drops sharply by March, when lake and land temperatures nearly equalize. In winter, the heavy lake-effect snowfall is augmented by snowfall from sometimes-strong low-pressure systems (mid-latitude [[cyclone]]s) that often converge on the [[Great Lakes]] and areas further east.\n\nOverall, Parry Sound experiences a typical humid continental, cool-summer climate type in terms of temperatures - but a highly unusual climate regime in precipitation and cloudiness; the year's driest months are generally from March through July, while its wettest months are from September to January, with autumnal lake effect producing cloudy skies and heavy rainfall from September into November, followed by extremely heavy snowfall in December and January.\n\nThe highest temperature ever recorded in Parry Sound was {{convert|37.8|C}} on July 6, 1921. The coldest temperature ever recorded was {{convert|-41.1|C|0}} on February 12. 1967.<ref name=\"July 1921\"/><ref name=\"February 1967\"/>\n\n{{Weather box\n|location = Parry Sound, 1981\u22122010 normals, extremes 1875\u2212present\n|metric first = Y\n|single line = Y\n|Jan record high C = 13.9\n|Feb record high C = 14.4\n|Mar record high C = 27.0\n|Apr record high C = 31.0\n|May record high C = 32.5\n|Jun record high C = 36.1\n|Jul record high C = 37.8\n|Aug record high C = 37.2\n|Sep record high C = 35.0\n|Oct record high C = 28.9\n|Nov record high C = 21.7\n|Dec record high C = 15.5\n|year record high C = 37.8\n|Jan high C = \u22124.4\n|Feb high C = \u22122.2\n|Mar high C = 2.6\n|Apr high C = 10.5\n|May high C = 16.9\n|Jun high C = 21.1\n|Jul high C = 25.1\n|Aug high C = 23.8\n|Sep high C = 19.0\n|Oct high C = 12.4\n|Nov high C = 5.1\n|Dec high C = -1.4\n|year high C = 10.7\n|Jan mean C = -9.0\n|Feb mean C = -6.8\n|Mar mean C = -2.2\n|Apr mean C = 5.7\n|May mean C = 11.8\n|Jun mean C = 16.2\n|Jul mean C = 20.2\n|Aug mean C = 19.2\n|Sep mean C = 14.8\n|Oct mean C = 8.4\n|Nov mean C = 1.9\n|Dec mean C = -5.2\n|year mean C = 6.3\n|Jan low C = \u221213.5\n|Feb low C = \u221211.4\n|Mar low C = \u22127.0\n|Apr low C = 0.9\n|May low C = 6.7\n|Jun low C = 11.2\n|Jul low C = 15.3\n|Aug low C = 14.6\n|Sep low C = 10.5\n|Oct low C = 4.4\n|Nov low C = \u22121.3\n|Dec low C = \u22128.9\n|year low C = 1.8\n|Jan record low C = \u221238.9\n|Feb record low C = \u221241.1\n|Mar record low C = \u221234.4\n|Apr record low C = \u221222.8\n|May record low C = \u22128.9\n|Jun record low C = -0.6\n|Jul record low C = 2.8\n|Aug record low C = 0.6\n|Sep record low C = \u22124.4\n|Oct record low C = \u221212.2\n|Nov record low C = \u221228.9\n|Dec record low C = \u221237.8\n|year record low C = \u221241.1\n|precipitation colour = green\n|Jan precipitation mm = 107.0\n|Feb precipitation mm = 80.3\n|Mar precipitation mm = 78.7\n|Apr precipitation mm = 71.4\n|May precipitation mm = 83.4\n|Ju